#: app/data/game_options.py:8
msgid "Empire Advantages — Random Method"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:14
msgid ""
"Each player is dealt 2 Empire Advantage cards at the start of the game "
"and keeps 1 (the other is discarded face down). A Replicator player "
"(40.0) receives 2 Replicator Empire Advantage cards instead. Cards are "
"placed face down and revealed when their condition is met. Do not use an "
"advantage if not playing with the rule it modifies."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:18
msgid "Empire Advantages — Balanced Method"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:24
msgid ""
"One more Empire Advantage card than the number of players is dealt face "
"up. Each player starts with 75 CP. Open CP bidding begins for each card "
"in turn until no one is willing to beat the highest bid. The winner "
"subtracts their bid from starting CP and picks the card. When one player "
"remains, they choose from the two remaining cards."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:28 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1296
msgid "Alien Technology Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:33
msgid ""
"When a player colonizes or captures a Deep Space barren planet, they may "
"draw 2 Alien Technology cards. If a card does not apply to their empire, "
"it may be revealed and discarded for a different one. The player must pay"
" 10 CP next Economic Phase to keep a chosen card, otherwise it is "
"discarded. With Non-Player Aliens (18.0), there is no cost. Cards are "
"placed face down and revealed when their condition is met."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:37 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1332
msgid "Crew Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:42
msgid ""
"Every even-numbered Economic Phase (2, 4, 6...), each player draws 2 Crew"
" Cards, keeps 1, discards the other face down. Crew Cards are assigned to"
" Groups during the same Economic Phase, providing unique combat bonuses. "
"Each player may have up to 5 Crew Cards in play. Can be used in addition "
"to or separately from Ship Experience (37.0); if used together, bonuses "
"are cumulative."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:46 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1408
msgid "Merchant Ship Pipelines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:51
msgid ""
"MS Pipelines are non-combat ships forming trade networks. They move 1 hex"
" per turn and cost no maintenance. Trade Networks: any Colony connected "
"to the Homeworld by an unbroken chain of MS Pipelines produces +1 CP per "
"Economic Phase. Movement Bonus: any unit starting its movement on a "
"friendly MS Pipeline chain may move 1 additional hex along the chain. MS "
"Pipelines survive Black Holes and allow ships to ignore Nebulae and "
"Asteroids for movement purposes along the chain."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:55 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1456
msgid "Defense Satellite Networks"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:60
msgid ""
"DSNs are stationary defense units (B4-1-x2) built at any friendly Colony "
"with income (not new or blockaded). Requires Ship Size 2 technology. DSNs"
" cannot move, cost no maintenance, and are not built by Shipyards. Each "
"Colony is limited to 1 DSN and 1 Base/Starbase per hex. DSNs participate "
"in combat like other Groups but may not retreat and cannot be boarded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:64
msgid "Carriers, Fighters & Point Defense"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:69
msgid ""
"Carriers (CV) hold up to 3 Fighter Squadrons. Carriers participate in "
"combat but cannot be targeted until all their Fighters are destroyed "
"(even if the CV is screened). Fighters are purchased in squadrons, cannot"
" move on their own, and can transfer between ships/planets. Fighter tech "
"improves their Attack and Defense. Point Defense is a Scout-only "
"technology giving them A-Class rating and higher Attack vs. Fighters "
"only; vs. other ships they fire at normal E-Class. Fighters at level 2-3 "
"get +1 Defense against PD."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:73 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1623
msgid "Raiders: Cloaking & Scanners"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:78
msgid ""
"Cloaking (levels 1-2) allows Raiders to move through occupied hexes "
"without stopping or triggering combat, occupy hexes without blockading, "
"and retreat before combat starts. In combat, cloaked Raiders fire at "
"A-Class with +1 Attack on the first round. Scanners (levels 1-2) on "
"Destroyers (and Advanced Bases) detect Raiders of equal or lower Cloaking"
" level, negating cloak advantages. Cloaking does not work in Nebulae."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:82 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1689
msgid "Mines & Minesweepers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:87
msgid ""
"Mines are placed at any friendly-occupied hex (including enemy Colonies)."
" They move 1 hex max, cost no maintenance, and detonate automatically "
"when enemy ships enter, destroying one ship each (regardless of Hull "
"Size). Mines must detonate and cannot choose targets. Minesweepers "
"(levels 1-3) remove 1/2/3 Mines each before detonation. Mines only work "
"on cloaked Raiders if a Destroyer with appropriate Scanner is present."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:91 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1753
msgid "Aliens (Non-Player Aliens)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:96
msgid ""
"When a Deep Space barren planet is revealed, random NPA ships are drawn "
"and placed on it (4 ships, or per Planet Attribute if using 26.0). NPAs "
"have Tactics 1, Security Forces 1, and attack any ship entering their "
"hex. Hull Size 2 NPAs have Scanner 1 and PD 1. NPAs never leave their hex"
" or retreat. A planet is conquered when its last NPA ship is destroyed. "
"The first non-team player to the active player's left controls the NPAs "
"in combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:100 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1798
msgid "Boarding & Capturing Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:105
msgid ""
"Boarding Ships (BD) can capture enemy ships. The attack compares the BD's"
" Attack Strength vs. the target's Hull Size (ignoring most tech "
"modifiers, except Experience and Security Forces). If the roll succeeds, "
"the ship is immediately captured. BDs always hit on 1, fire as F-Class in"
" terrain, and may not mount Attack tech. Carriers, Bases, Starbases, "
"DSNs, Titans, DMs, Colonies, Amoebas, and Replicator ships cannot be "
"captured. Captured ships can be scrapped to steal one level of technology"
" per ship."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:115
msgid ""
"Defensive technology against Boarding Ships. Security Forces 1 gives all "
"ships +1 Hull Size when targeted by a boarding attack (making capture "
"harder). Security Forces 2 doubles this to +2. All NPA ships (18.0) are "
"equipped with Security Forces 1. The bonus is automatic and does not "
"require upgrading existing ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:119 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1931
msgid "Transports & Ground Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:124
msgid ""
"Transports carry up to 6 Ground Units (Infantry, Space Marines, Heavy "
"Infantry, Militia, Grav Armor, Cyber Armor). Ground Units take and defend"
" Colonies via planetary invasion after winning space combat. Colonies "
"receive free Militia (1 per CP) when invaded. Ground Combat 2 unlocks "
"Space Marines and Heavy Infantry. Ground Combat 3 unlocks Grav Armor "
"(support ability) and upgrades Transports to Drop Ships (Defense 2, "
"first-round landing). Bombardment from space can reduce Colonies before "
"landing."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:128 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2267
msgid "Titans"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:133
msgid ""
"Massive warships requiring Ship Size 7 technology. Each hit from a Titan "
"does 2 damage to a single ship (1 attack per round). Titans may never be "
"screened (due to size) or retreat from combat. They are immune to "
"boarding. Fighters get +1 Attack Strength vs. Titans. Mines do 1 damage "
"each (5 Mines needed to kill a Titan). Titans can carry 3 Fighters like "
"Carriers when Fighter tech is researched. Titans destroy Colonies and "
"planets on bombardment."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:137 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2316
msgid "Flagships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:142
msgid ""
"Each player begins with one named Flagship (Enterprise, Victory, Thunder "
"Child, Argo, Fearless, or Eagle). Counts as Hull Size 3 for upgrading and"
" damage. Pays no maintenance. May carry Exploration 1 and Fast 1 once "
"researched. Technology upgraded normally. Can gain Experience. If "
"destroyed, it can never be rebuilt. If captured, the capturing player may"
" use it. With Alternate Empires (24.0), Flagships gain random special "
"abilities like BCs/BBs/DNs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:146 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2352
msgid "Alternate Empires"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:151
msgid ""
"Up to 2 players use empires with alternate ship costs, abilities, and a "
"new unit type: Missile Boats. Missile Boats fire one Missile per round at"
" A-Class (early in combat), doing 2 damage to ships or 1 to Titans. "
"Alternate Empires cannot build Titans (except War Sun advantage) or "
"CVs/BVs. Their Fighters do not need carrying ships and function as "
"combat-capable units. Jammer technology on Cruisers counters Missiles. At"
" Ship Size 4/AC 1, BCs/BBs/DNs draw a random special ability."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:155 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2505
msgid "Additional Terrain"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:160
msgid ""
"Umbrella option adding new terrain types to the Deep Space System "
"markers. Enable specific terrain types below (Cosmic Storms, Folds in "
"Space, Space Stations, Pulsars, Quantum Filaments, Regional Maps, Space "
"Pirates, Quasars). Terrain tiles replace some standard System markers "
"during setup. Each sub-option adds its own counters and rules."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:164 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2761
msgid "Deep Space Planet Attributes"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:170
msgid ""
"Each Deep Space barren planet gets an Attribute counter (drawn when the "
"planet is flipped) specifying the number of NPA ships and Heavy Infantry "
"defending it. Requires Non-Player Aliens (18.0). Adds 20 new NPA counters"
" (A5-1-x2 or E7-1-x2) to the supply. Hull Size 2 NPAs get Scanner 1. "
"Planets scanned with Exploration tech (9.8) have their counter returned "
"face down without being drawn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:174 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2792
msgid "Scenario Modifier Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:179
msgid ""
"At setup, 2 Scenario Modifier Cards are randomly drawn (one at a time). "
"If the second conflicts with the first, it is discarded and replaced. "
"Both cards remain in effect for the entire game, changing rules or "
"victory conditions. If used with Empire Advantages (10.0), the Scenario "
"Modifiers are selected first."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:183 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2516
msgid "Cosmic Storms"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:189
msgid ""
"Two types: Plasma Storms and Ion Storms. Both move one hex at the end of "
"each Economic Phase (roll a die: 1-6 moves, 7-10 stays). Plasma Storms "
"destroy ships costing 9 CP or less, Space Wrecks, and Minerals on "
"contact. Ion Storms double all combat damage inside them; leaving an Ion "
"Storm requires a die roll (9-10 = stuck for the turn). Storms only enter "
"empty Deep Space hexes (no Nebulae, Asteroids, etc.). Destroyed by Black "
"Holes. Doomsday Machines unaffected."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:193 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2577
msgid "Folds in Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:199
msgid ""
"Permanent spatial shortcuts. Ships never stop in a Fold hex — they pass "
"straight through without spending movement. A ship adjacent to a Fold is "
"considered adjacent to all hexes on the other side. Exploration tech can "
"scan through Folds. MS Pipelines can trace chains through Folds. If a "
"Fold is explored and found adjacent to another revealed Fold, remove it "
"from the game. A ship pushed into a Fold by a Lost in Space marker is "
"returned to its entry hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:203 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2592
msgid "Space Stations"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:209
msgid ""
"Hostile automated platforms (A5-1-x1 or A6-2-x2) that do not move and "
"must be defeated in combat. All Space Stations have Point Defense 2 and "
"Scanner 1, and cannot be boarded. Reward for destruction depends on type:"
" A6-2-x2 yields 2 free Alien Tech cards; A5-1-x1 yields 5 CP or 10 CP (if"
" not using Alien Tech cards)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:213 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2622
msgid "Pulsars"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:219
msgid ""
"Color-coded terrain (Blue, Red, Green). Ships that spend an entire turn "
"not moving inside a Pulsar become Charged. Charged ships gain a bonus "
"upon leaving: Blue = +1 Movement that turn, Red = +1 Attack Strength that"
" turn, Green = +1 Defense Strength that turn. All friendly ships in a "
"Pulsar must leave simultaneously at the slowest ship's speed. Ships may "
"never retreat from battle in a Pulsar."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:223 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2669
msgid "Quantum Filaments"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:229
msgid ""
"Extremely dense gravity fields. Ships must spend 1 additional hex of "
"movement to enter. Ships that can only move 1 hex per turn cannot enter. "
"Cloaking technology does not work inside a Quantum Filament. Boarding "
"Ships may not perform boarding attacks inside. Fighters cannot be used in"
" combat. Ships may retreat into a Quantum Filament or enter via Reaction "
"Movement (35.0). Alternate Empire Fighters treat them as Super Novae."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:233 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2695
msgid "Regional Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:239
msgid ""
"When a ship explores a hex containing a Regional Map counter, the "
"exploring player may look at all adjacent face-down System markers. They "
"may reveal or leave them face down, just like using Exploration "
"technology. If peeked at using Exploration tech or a Regional Map, the "
"counter must be left face down until actually entered."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:243 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2703
msgid "Space Pirates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:249
msgid ""
"Interstellar nomads (A5-0-x1, Move 4, Fast 1, Tactics 0). When revealed, "
"the player must fight or hire the Pirate. Hiring costs 10 CP (paid next "
"Economic Phase). A hired Pirate is controlled by the player, moves at "
"speed 4, stacks and defends with friendly ships but attacks alone. Self-"
"destructs if captured. Cannot gain technology or Empire Advantages. No "
"maintenance. One Pirate per player max. Removed if a DM reveals or "
"approaches the Pirate."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:253 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2753
msgid "Quasars"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:259
msgid ""
"In combat at a Quasar hex, the Defense Strength and Defense technology of"
" all units are set to zero. This represents the unexplainable effects of "
"the quasar's powerful radio waves on all combat systems."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:263 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2810
msgid "The Galactic Capitol"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:269
msgid ""
"A neutral, highly developed planet placed in Deep Space. No combat ever "
"takes place in this hex — both combat and non-combat ships may pass "
"through. Players may trade with the Galactic Capitol by connecting their "
"Homeworld via MS Pipelines, yielding 5 CP (not 1) per Economic Phase. "
"Multiple empires may trade simultaneously. Replicators cannot gain RPs "
"here since combat is forbidden. The Traders Empire Advantage earns 6 CP "
"instead."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:273 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2858
msgid "Warp Points"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:278
msgid ""
"6 Warp Point markers (3 matching pairs) are mixed into the Deep Space "
"System markers. Once a matching pair is discovered, they act as adjacent "
"hexes for all purposes: movement, MS Pipeline chains, retreating. The "
"third marker of the same number is discarded. A ship at a Warp Point may "
"move to the matching Warp Point's System and continue as if the two "
"Systems were adjacent. Reaction moves (35.0) may NOT be made through Warp"
" Points."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:287
msgid ""
"1-3 DMs are mixed into Deep Space System markers (players agree on the "
"number). A DM is C-Class, gets 2 attacks per round, Attack 9, Defense 2, "
"Hull Size 3. DMs move each turn toward the nearest planet/asteroid/ship "
"(up to 2 hexes). They destroy any Colony or planet they land on. In "
"competitive play, DMs have Tactics 2 and Scanner 2; a roll of 1 counts as"
" a hit. Mines detonate on DMs. DMs are immune to Fighters. Destroying a "
"DM gives a double roll on the Space Wreck table."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:291 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2954
msgid "Instant Technology Upgrade"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:296
msgid ""
"When a player purchases a new technology level, all existing ships are "
"instantly upgraded to that level at no extra cost. This removes the need "
"to track which ships have which technology level. Simplifies bookkeeping "
"but makes technology purchases more powerful since the entire fleet "
"benefits immediately."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:300 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2962
msgid "Black Hole Slingshot"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:305
msgid ""
"A ship entering a revealed Black Hole hex may declare a \"slingshot\" "
"attempt before rolling for survival. The survival roll is modified by +2 "
"(making destruction 20% more likely). If the ship survives, it gains +1 "
"Movement for that turn only. This bonus cannot be combined with MS "
"Pipeline movement benefits. The decision must be declared before the die "
"is rolled."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:309 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2970
msgid "Research Gearing Limits"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:315
msgid ""
"A player may only spend 10 more CP on research than they spent the "
"previous turn. For example, if a player spent 15 CP on research, they may"
" spend 0 to 25 next turn. If they spend 0, the following turn they can "
"spend at most 10. This prevents empires from going from zero to massive "
"research investment in a single turn, encouraging steady research "
"spending."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:319 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2980
msgid "Unpredictable Research"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:324
msgid ""
"Instead of purchasing technology directly, players spend CP in 5 CP "
"grants, each allowing one die roll. For every 10 CP spent on a "
"technology, roll two dice. Results are summed; if the total meets or "
"exceeds the technology cost, it is acquired immediately. Otherwise, keep "
"the running total and add to it next turn. Funding must be specific to "
"each technology type (Tactics, Movement, Attack, etc.). Adds uncertainty "
"to research."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:328 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3016
msgid "Terraforming Nebulae"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:334
msgid ""
"Terraforming 2 technology may be purchased after Terraforming 1. A Miner "
"in a Nebula connected by an MS Pipeline chain to the Homeworld collects 5"
" CP per Economic Phase (one Miner per Nebula). The Miner must have been "
"built with or upgraded to Terraforming 2. Income from Nebulae is not "
"modified by Variants, Resource Cards, Empire Advantages, or Alien "
"Technologies."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:338 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3048
msgid "Reaction Movement"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:344
msgid ""
"Requires Exploration 2 technology. After an opponent finishes moving, "
"ships with the React ability in an adjacent hex may move 1 hex to join a "
"battle before combat resolves. React ability is gained at: Move 3+ (SCs, "
"DDs, CAs, Rs), Move 4+ (Flagships, BCs, BDs, MBs), Move 5+ (BBs, CVs, "
"BVs, Unique Ships, Transports), Move 6+ (DNs, Minesweepers). Only 1 hex "
"of reaction per player turn. Cannot react through Warp Points."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:348 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3103
msgid "Facilities (IC/RC/LC/TC)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:354
msgid ""
"Adds 4 types of Facilities built at Colonies for 5 CP each (no benefit "
"the turn built). Homeworlds use 20 CP (not 30) and start with 1 RC and 1 "
"LC (if playing with LCs). Each Colony supports 1 Facility; Homeworlds "
"support 2. Facilities are destroyed when a Colony is eliminated or "
"captured by Ground Units. Enable specific Facility types below (IC, RC, "
"LC, TC). For a simpler game, players may agree to skip LCs and/or TCs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:358 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3342
msgid "Ship Experience & Military Academies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:364
msgid ""
"5 Experience levels per Group: Green, Skilled, Veteran, Elite, Legendary."
" Experience is tracked per Group (not per ship). Groups gain Experience "
"by destroying/capturing units (die roll ≤ 2× target Hull Size). Higher "
"Experience gives +1 Attack vs. lower Experience Groups, and -1 Attack "
"against Groups 2+ levels above. Groups 3+ levels above cannot be fired "
"upon (except at the lowest Experienced target). Elite/ Legendary Groups "
"pay half maintenance. Military Academies (levels 1-2) improve starting "
"Experience of new ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:373
msgid ""
"3 progressive levels (10 CP each) unlocking advanced ship types and "
"technologies. Cannot be researched until a player actually builds a Ship "
"Size 4+ ship. Levels must be purchased in order. Each level opens new "
"units and upgrades (see sub-options AC 1/2/3). \"Advanced\" means a non-"
"advanced unit may be upgraded; \"X\" at the end means a non-advanced unit"
" may NOT be upgraded to that type."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:377 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3722
msgid "Resource Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:382
msgid ""
"Each player gets their own deck of Resource Cards (split equally). Draw 3"
" at game start, then 1 per Economic Phase (max 6 in hand). Each card can "
"be played for its Event OR discarded for its CP value. Events are played "
"in reverse turn order. 4 Cancel Cards in the deck can negate other cards."
" Mission Cards require completing an objective on the map for a reward "
"(rolled on a table). Cards add flavor, unpredictability, and strategic "
"choices to each Economic Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:386 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3906
msgid "Replicators"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:392
msgid ""
"One player plays as self-replicating Von-Neumann Machines with completely"
" different mechanics. Replicators have their own Empire Advantages, "
"Production Sheet, and ship types. They do not collect income or use CP — "
"instead, Colonies at Full growth produce ships directly. Colony Depletion"
" occurs each Economic Phase (closest Full Colony is consumed). Research "
"is via Research Points (RP, max 15) earned through encounters, not "
"purchased. Ship technology (Attack, Defense, Move) scales with RP "
"accumulated. Cannot use Colony Ships, Bases, Starbases, DSNs, Shipyards, "
"or MS Pipelines."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:396 app/data/master_rulebook.py:4280
msgid "Unique Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:402
msgid ""
"Each player designs a custom ship before the game starts (6 identical "
"counters). The design sets Weapon Class, Attack, Defense, and Hull Size "
"from cost tables. Up to 2 special abilities may be added (same ability "
"cannot be chosen twice). Min cost 5 CP (9 CP if carrying Exploration). "
"Ship Size technology determines the max CP cost. The design may be "
"changed anytime (costs 5 CP, no Unique Ships currently built). All Unique"
" Ships get the React ability at Move 5."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:406
msgid "Industrial Centers (IC)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:412
msgid ""
"Each IC provides 5 CP per Economic Phase. This CP may be accumulated and "
"used like any other CP. ICs do not allow players to exceed the 30 CP "
"carry-over limitation per Economic Phase. When a Colony with an IC "
"generates income, the entire amount is CP (the Homeworld always produces "
"20 CP plus whatever its Facilities generate). Income from MS Pipelines "
"and Minerals is always CP regardless of Facilities present."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:416
msgid "Research Centers (RC)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:422
msgid ""
"Each RC provides 5 Research Points (RP) per Economic Phase, tracked on "
"the Production Sheet. Only RP can be used to purchase technology (not "
"CP). CP cannot be converted to RP. Up to 30 RP can be carried over "
"between Economic Phases. This forces players to plan research spending "
"more deliberately, since technology can only come from RC output. "
"Homeworlds start with 1 RC, producing 20 CP + 5 RP on the first Economic "
"Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:426
msgid "Logistic Centers (LC)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:432
msgid ""
"Each LC provides 5 Logistic Points (LP) per Economic Phase. LP is used "
"instead of CP to pay maintenance. Ships must be within Supply Range "
"(determined by Supply Range technology) of a friendly Colony to receive "
"supply. Out of Supply Groups: pay no maintenance, move only 1 hex per "
"turn, suffer -3 Attack and -3 Defense (min 0/1). LP is also converted to "
"groups of 5 placed on the board as supply counters. Transports can carry "
"up to 30 LP. LP can be converted from CP at 3:1 if LP runs short."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:436
msgid "Temporal Centers (TC)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:442
msgid ""
"Each TC provides 5 Temporal Points (TP) per Economic Phase. TP is spent "
"to activate effects from the Temporal Effect Table (p.46) via Temporal "
"Engines installed on Bases, Advanced Bases, Starbases, and Shipyards. At "
"game start, one random ship type also carries Temporal Engines. Effects "
"include extra movement, combat bonuses, rerouting targeting, and more. "
"Each effect can be used on a specific ship only once per turn, but "
"multiple effects may be stacked. No limit on TP carry-over between "
"rounds."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:446 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3506
msgid "Advanced Construction 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:452
msgid ""
"Costs 10 CP. Unlocks: DestroyerX (DDX, upgraded DD with +1 Attack/Defense"
" and Heavy Warheads), Advanced Bases (Bases with Exploration 2 and "
"Scanners, buildable at any MS Pipeline hex even without a planet), "
"Tractor Beams (mountable on any ship, independent research), Shield "
"Projectors (mountable on any ship, independent research), Attack 4 on "
"Titans and Starbases only (requires Attack 3 first)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:456 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3522
msgid "Advanced Construction 2"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:462
msgid ""
"Costs 10 CP. Unlocks: Starbases (A7-3-x4, 2 attacks/round, upgradable "
"from Advanced Bases for 12 CP, mount Attack 4 and Exploration 2 "
"automatically, cannot move), Cyber Armor (counts as 3 Grav Armor in "
"ground combat), Battle Carriers (BV, carry 6 Fighters, treated as CVs, "
"can get Fast 2), Fighter 4 (Fighter tech upgrade), and 4 MinerX counters "
"(Miners that auto-upgrade Move and Terraforming tech, not limited to Move"
" 1)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:466 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3530
msgid "Advanced Construction 3"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:472
msgid ""
"Costs 10 CP. Unlocks: RaiderX (RX, upgraded Raider with +1 "
"Attack/Defense, Fast 2, can carry 1 Ground Unit and serve as Drop Ship), "
"ScoutX (SCX, Group #7 with Movement 3 levels above current tech, up to "
"Move 7, acts as a fast Scout), and Advanced Flagship (upgrade cost 3 CP, "
"gains all current tech levels, may pick one special ability from the "
"Unique Ship Table)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:476
msgid "\"Sinister\" Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:481
msgid ""
"A player wins by eliminating the Homeworld of the player on their left "
"(not any opponent). This creates two fronts per player (one offensive, "
"one defensive) and reduces the likelihood of two players ganging up on a "
"third."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:485
msgid "Simultaneous Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:490
msgid ""
"Experienced players conduct their turns simultaneously. Players only wait"
" for each other when there is direct interaction (combat, same hex) or to"
" keep everyone in the same Economic Phase. Switch to sequential turns "
"when only two rows of unexplored Deep Space remain between players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:494
msgid "Quick Start (AGT)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:499
msgid ""
"After setting up, flip all Home System markers and place a full-strength "
"Colony on all non-barren planets. Players do not start with any Colony "
"Ships. 10 CP planets grow to 5 CP like any other Colony, then to 10 CP "
"the following phase (place a flipped Colony Ship on top until 10 CP is "
"reached)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:503
msgid "Handicap Rule"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:508
msgid ""
"Gives a less-experienced player a small advantage by increasing their CP "
"income during the early game. During each Economic Phase, the income of "
"that player's Colonies increases by two steps (e.g., a Colony Ship "
"becomes a \"1 Colony\" with a \"3 Colony\" marker on top)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:512
msgid "Variable but Balanced Home Systems"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:517
msgid ""
"All players set aside specific markers from their Home Systems and from a"
" pool of new \"v\" markers. These are organized into 14 stacks of one "
"counter type per player. Players collectively choose 6 stacks randomly "
"and blindly, then each takes their 6 markers and shuffles them into their"
" Home System markers before setup. All players have the same composition "
"but no one knows which specific markers are in play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:521
msgid "Uneasy Alliance"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:526
msgid ""
"Team variant. Teammates may never stack units in the same hex and may not"
" use each other's MS Pipelines. Teammates may not capture each other's "
"Colonies with Ground Units (21.0) or use Boarding Ships (19.0) on allies."
" Teammates win or lose together."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:530
msgid "Blood Brothers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:536
msgid ""
"Team variant. Teammates execute their turns at the same time. They may "
"stack together, attack together, and use each other's MS Pipelines for "
"movement. However, they may not share research or CPs. Allies may never "
"bombard Colonies originally colonized by their teammate. Teammates win or"
" lose together."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:546
msgid ""
"Giant Space Amoebas are pre-placed in Deep Space between Home Systems. "
"They multiply and attack human players during the game. Unlike the solo "
"scenario, no rule restrictions apply (Titans, Ground Combat, Facilities, "
"etc. can all be used). Players must pay maintenance as usual. "
"Minesweepers double as Science Vessels (SV) to research Amoebas: each SV "
"in an Amoeba hex rolls a die for Research Points. After 10 RP total, a "
"player rolls on the Amoeba Strength Table to determine the Amoeba type "
"for the entire game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:550
msgid "Quick Start Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:555
msgid ""
"After set up, all System markers of the player's color are flipped and "
"all non-barren planets have a full-strength Colony placed on them. The "
"player does not start with any Colony Ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:559
msgid "Ship Build Requirement Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:564
msgid ""
"Players may not research Fighter Technology until a BC, BB, or DN from "
"either side has been in combat with another player (not aliens). Players "
"may not research Cloaking until a DD or larger ship from either side has "
"been in combat with another player. Once the condition is met, all "
"players may research the technology."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:568
msgid "Low Maintenance Game Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:573
msgid ""
"All maintenance costs are halved (round down). When calculating "
"maintenance, add up the total you would normally pay, then divide by 2. "
"Encourages building ships early, attacking early, and fielding larger "
"fleets."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:577
msgid "Heavy Terrain Game Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:582
msgid ""
"When a \"Danger!\" or \"Lost in Space\" counter is flipped, the hex is "
"not left empty. Instead, a new Deep Space System marker is drawn from the"
" unused ones and placed face down in the hex. Once all markers are used, "
"the space is left empty. If the marker was flipped by scanning, the new "
"marker may be explored but not scanned again that turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:586
msgid "Variable 3-Player Map"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:591
msgid ""
"All Home System and Deep Space markers are mixed together and randomly "
"placed across the entire map. Players place their home planets randomly "
"using a D20. This often leads to unbalanced maps, but diplomacy and "
"alliances become part of the challenge: weaker positions can gang up on "
"stronger ones."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:595
msgid "More Aliens"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:601
msgid ""
"The Barren Planet in each player's Home System has aliens, as if it were "
"a Deep Space barren planet. An Alien Technology Card is gained from "
"colonizing it."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:610
msgid ""
"Whenever a \"Danger!\" marker is flipped, one die is rolled for all "
"exploring ships. Ships are only eliminated on a roll of 9-10 (instead of "
"the normal rules). On 1-8, there is no effect."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:619
msgid "The income from all Mineral counters is doubled."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:623
msgid "Slow Scientists"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:628
msgid "The research cost of all technologies is increased by 5 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:637
msgid "The research cost of all technologies is decreased by 5 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:646
msgid "All units have their Attack Strength increased by 1."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:650
msgid "Rich Colonies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:655
msgid ""
"All Colonies (including Home planets) that would normally produce at "
"least 1 CP have their income increased by 3 CP. In the case of ground "
"combat, Militia still only equal the face value of the Colony's CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:659
msgid "Head Start"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:664
msgid ""
"Each player starts the game with 75 CP (or some agreed amount) to spend "
"only on technology before receiving starting units. No more than 2 levels"
" of Ship Size or Move technology and no more than 1 level of any other "
"technology may be purchased. Up to 10 CP may be carried over as normal CP"
" into the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:668
msgid "Colony Points (Short Game Victory Condition)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:673
msgid ""
"Alternate multiplayer victory condition. In addition to Homeworld "
"destruction, a player wins by scoring 3 Colony Points. A Colony Point is "
"earned by: destroying (not just damaging) another player's Colony "
"(permanent, includes ground combat capture); having a 5 CP Colony in Deep"
" Space or an opponent's Home System (not permanent — lost if the Colony "
"is lost); or capturing a Colony that grows to 5 CP outside its owner's "
"Home System. A player wins instantly upon scoring their third Colony "
"Point, even mid-turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:677
msgid "Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:682
msgid ""
"When a player eliminates another player, they become the victor. All of "
"the eliminated player's pieces and Colonies are removed. The victor gets "
"a 30 CP bonus in the next Economic Phase. If the conquered player had "
"technology the victor does not possess, the victor may choose one level "
"of two separate technologies and mark them as researched. Re-colonized "
"Homeworlds act as normal Colonies (at most 5 CP)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:686
msgid "Optional First Player Bidding in Doomsday Machine Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:691
msgid ""
"The DM starts the game as first player and will bid when appropriate. The"
" DM bid is resolved after human players complete their Econ Phases. The "
"DM only bids if a DM is on the board. Bid amount: lower of 2d10 (free CP "
"for the DM). If both dice show the same number, add the result to another"
" lower-of-2d10 roll (exploding doubles — repeat if doubles again). If a "
"human player wins the bid, they become first player and may commit to "
"their own play order during each Econ Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:695
msgid "Black Hole Jumping"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/game_options.py:700
msgid ""
"Technology provided by the Galactic Capitol in the Solitaire Alien Empire"
" VP scenario. Two levels costing 20 CP (level 1) and 40 CP (level 2). "
"Level 1: ships may freely enter a Black Hole without rolling for "
"survival. Level 2: ships treat all face-up Black Holes and Warp Points on"
" the map as connected — they may jump between them as if those hexes were"
" adjacent, per normal Warp Point rules. On Hard difficulty, Movement 3 "
"must be researched before gaining this technology. Must be noted on the "
"Production Sheet if researched."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:9
msgid "Master Rule Book Foreword"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:12
msgid ""
"This rule book is a consolidation of all the rules for Space Empires 4X, "
"Close Encounters, Replicators, and All Good Things. All expansions are "
"necessary to take advantage of all the options found here. References to "
"the Competitive Scenario Book (CSB) and the Solo/Co-Op Scenario Book "
"(SSB) will be notated accordingly, e.g., (SSB 8.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:14
msgid ""
"Non-Player Alien (NPA): Combat ships that defend Deep Space barren "
"planets. Permanent Terrain: System Markers that stay in the hex in which "
"they are revealed (Planets, Asteroids, Black Holes, etc)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:20
msgid "Game Overview"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:23
msgid ""
"Space Empires is a classic \"4X\" game: eXplore, eXpand, eXploit, and "
"eXterminate. Each player will grow a space Empire and will attempt to win"
" by eliminating other players. The time scale of this game is very large "
"– at least an Earth year in-between Economic Phases. The Scenario Books "
"provide game setup details and additional rules based on the chosen "
"scenario."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:28
msgid "Base Rules and Optional Rules"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:31
msgid ""
"If you have made it this far in the series, there is little need to roll "
"rules out slowly. These are organized into Base Rules, which I (Jim "
"Krohn) recommend always playing with (with experienced players), and "
"Optional Rules which can be added in for flavor or change of pace. Not "
"all Optional Rules are created equal. For instance, I rarely play with "
"Unique Ships (while for other players they are considered a must), I "
"sometimes play with Resource Cards, and I often play with Alternate "
"Empires. Play the game anyway you want using the rules that you like the "
"most!"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:36
msgid "Glossary of Commonly Used Terms:"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:39
msgid ""
"Colonize: The process of putting a Colony on a planet in the Movement "
"Phase (4.4) or Combat Phases (5.10.3, 21.13) and continuing that process "
"in the Economic Phase (7.0).\n"
"\n"
"Combat-Capable Units: These include all units with an Attack Strength.\n"
"\n"
"Construction Point (CP): Homeworlds and Colonies produce Construction "
"Points. Construction Points are used in the Economic Phase to purchase "
"units, maintain spaceships, and develop technology. A Production Sheet "
"has been provided to facilitate keeping track of CP.\n"
"\n"
"Deep Space: Non-Home System hexes where Deep Space system markers are "
"placed at the start of the game.\n"
"\n"
"Enemy: A unit that is an opponent to a given player. This includes Alien "
"ships (18.0, SSB 4.0), Doomsday Machines (29.0, SSB 2.0), and Amoebas "
"(SSB 3.0, CSB 10.0).\n"
"\n"
"Fleet: All ships belonging to one Empire within a hex.\n"
"\n"
"Group: One to six units of the same type and technology level, "
"represented by a Group counter (2.3). Counters do not always represent "
"single units, but have a numeral marker stacked underneath them to "
"indicate the number of units in that Group (from one to six). Colony "
"Ships, Miners, and MS Pipelines are the only exceptions to this rule as "
"they always represent a single ship.\n"
"\n"
"Home System: A group of hexes where the Homeworld (2.8) and Home System "
"markers (2.1) are placed during set up.\n"
"\n"
"Non-Combat Units: These units have no Attack Strength and include Colony "
"Ships, Miners, MS Pipelines and Decoys.\n"
"\n"
"Non-Player Alien (NPA): Combat ships that defend Deep Space barren "
"planets.\n"
"\n"
"Permanent Terrain: System Markers that stay in the hex in which they are "
"revealed (Planets, Asteroids, Black Holes, etc).\n"
"\n"
"Ships (Spaceships): Other than non-Group ships (2.6), ships are always "
"represented by a Group counter, even if only one ship is present (don't "
"be thrown by the term \"Group\").\n"
"\n"
"System: A vast zone of space, represented in this game by a single hex "
"printed on the game board.\n"
"\n"
"Unit: Ship, Ground Unit, Decoy, Miner, Colony Ship, MS Pipeline, "
"Shipyard, Base, Starbase, Missile, or Defense Satellite Network."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:67
msgid ""
"Deep Space: Non-Home System hexes where Deep Space system markers are "
"placed at the start of the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:73
msgid "Playing Pieces"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:76
msgid ""
"Each player should pick a color to represent their Empire and will "
"receive System and Group counters of their color."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:81
msgid "System Markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:84
msgid ""
"At setup, sort the System markers according to the border printed on "
"their back. The markers with white borders are Deep Space. The markers "
"with colored borders will populate each player's stellar neighborhood, "
"called the \"Home System.\" The red player will have red-bordered System "
"markers in their Home System, and so forth. System markers must be placed"
" randomly; their front-sides should remain unknown to all players. Turn "
"all the markers with the same-colored border face down, carefully mix "
"them, and randomly place them on the map board, one in each hex, inside "
"their Home System. Note: eight additional Home System markers have been "
"provided for each color. These are marked with a \"v\" on the front side."
" They should not be used unless using the Variable Home System Set Up "
"(CSB 1.1.13). The white System markers occupy the hexes between the Home "
"Systems of the players. Set aside any unused white System markers as they"
" will not be needed. See the Scenario Books for the exact details of "
"setup for each scenario."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:89
msgid "Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:92
msgid ""
"Planets have no effect on play until colonized (4.4.1). Terraforming "
"technology is required for colonizing Barren Planets (9.7). Barren "
"Planets in Deep Space are inhabited by uncooperative aliens (18.0)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:94
msgid "Fleet: All ships belonging to one Empire within a hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:100
msgid "Groups"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:103
msgid ""
"Group counters have pictures of units on them and represent 1-6 units of "
"the same type and technology level. Place a numeral marker underneath the"
" Group counter to indicate the number of units in the Group. Units of the"
" same type and technology may join and leave Groups as they choose at any"
" time (as counters allow). Group counters have two sides – the back side "
"is used to hide the unit's type and combat information. Group counters "
"and their numeral markers start with their identity hidden from other "
"players and are only revealed in combat. Some Replicator (40.0) Group "
"counters have a 1 in the upper-right corner to indicate that they have "
"Tactics 1 technology (9.3).\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: If there are two Cruisers with the same tech level in a Cruiser "
"Group, place a \"2\" numeral marker underneath the CA Group counter. Even"
" if only a single unit is in a Group, place a \"1\" numeral marker "
"underneath it. Other players won't know how many spaceships are in that "
"Group."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:110
msgid "Type"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:113
msgid ""
"The unit type is indicated by the large letters in the upper-left corner "
"of the counter."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:118 app/data/tables.py:456
msgid "Weapon Class"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:121
msgid ""
"This letter is used in determining which unit fires first in combat (an "
"A-Class fires first in combat before a B-Class)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:126 app/data/tables.py:467
msgid "Attack Strength"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:129
msgid ""
"The number needed to score a hit (a 4 means a player must roll a 4 or "
"less to hit a target)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:134 app/data/tables.py:481
msgid "Defense Strength"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:137
msgid ""
"Defense Strength is the number printed next to the Attack Strength. For "
"example, a Cruiser has a Defense Strength of 1. This number is subtracted"
" from the attacker's Attack Strength, so the higher this number the "
"harder it is to hit the unit in combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:142
msgid "Hull Size (aka Ship Size)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:145
msgid ""
"Hull Size is the number after the \"x\". Measured in Hull Points, it "
"indicates the number of hits required to destroy a unit in the Group. For"
" example, a Cruiser's Hull Size is \"2\", which means that two hits "
"destroy one Cruiser. Hull Size also determines the maintenance cost of a "
"unit, the level of technology it can utilize, and the construction "
"capacity needed to build it at a Shipyard. Notice that the Hull Size is "
"printed on the Group counter, but it applies to each unit within that "
"Group. Ground Units don't have Hulls, but for simplicity's sake they use "
"the same metric."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:150
msgid "Group Identification Number"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:153
msgid "Use this number to identify the Group on the Ship Technology Sheet."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:158
msgid "Numeral Markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:161
msgid ""
"Each Group in play must have ONE of these stacked underneath it to "
"indicate the number of units represented by the Group counter."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:166
msgid "Fleet Markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:169
msgid ""
"To help with crowding, three Fleet Markers have been provided for each "
"Empire. Fleet Displays are kept in clear view of all players. Any number "
"of a player's units may be placed on their Fleet Display and represented "
"by the corresponding Fleet Marker on the map. In all ways, a counter on a"
" player's Fleet Display is considered in the hex with the Fleet marker."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:174
msgid "Non-Group Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:177
msgid ""
"Colony Ships, MS Pipelines, and Miners are non-Group units. They always "
"represent a single ship – never place a numeral marker underneath them, "
"and always place them face up."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:182
msgid "Damage Markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:185
msgid ""
"Place damage markers on top of a Group to keep track of the hits applied "
"to this Group during the Combat Phase (5.6). These are removed at the "
"conclusion of the Combat Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:190
msgid "Homeworlds"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:193
msgid ""
"A Homeworld represents the player's home planet plus possible "
"installations on moons and planets within the same solar system. Each "
"player starts with one Homeworld from which they will explore the galaxy."
" A Homeworld produces 30 CP each Economic Phase. The 20 CP Homeworld "
"counter should be used when playing with the optional rules for "
"Facilities (36.0). Except as noted, rules that apply to Colonies also "
"apply to Homeworlds."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:198
msgid "Colony Number Counters"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:201
msgid ""
"These are numbered counters with the word \"Colony\" on them and are "
"placed on top of Colonies to track Colony growth on a planet. Several of "
"these are marked with the word \"Home\"; use them only when a Homeworld "
"takes damage."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:206
msgid "Additional Counters"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:209
msgid ""
"Counters that are labeled DYO on their revealed side are to cover "
"lost/damaged counters or to allow the players to add their own "
"unit/terrain rules to the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:214
msgid "Dice"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:217
msgid ""
"The game comes with 10-sided dice which are used for all rolls in the "
"game. On these dice, a 0 represents a 10."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:222
msgid "Sequence of Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:225
msgid ""
"For the first turn of the game, players roll a die to determine first "
"player; player order proceeds clockwise around the map board. After the "
"first three turns (B, C, D, below), Player Order is determined by bidding"
" in the Economic Phase (7.4). The Sequence of Play is as follows:\n"
"\n"
"A. Determine Player Order (First Turn Only – see above.)\n"
"\n"
"B. Turn One:\n"
"Player 1:\n"
"a. Movement Phase (4.0)\n"
"b. Combat Phase (5.0)\n"
"c. Exploration Phase (6.0)\n"
"Players 2-4: Same as Player 1\n"
"\n"
"C. Turn Two: (same as turn one)\n"
"\n"
"D. Turn Three: (same as turn one)\n"
"\n"
"E. Economic Phase: All players conduct this phase simultaneously, not in "
"player order (7.0).\n"
"\n"
"Keep track of the current turn using the Turn marker and the Turn Track "
"printed on the game board. After the Economic Phase, the Turn marker is "
"reset to 1. Continue until a winner is determined."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:247
msgid "Movement Phase"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:250 app/data/master_rulebook.py:341
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:494 app/data/master_rulebook.py:548
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:764 app/data/master_rulebook.py:800
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:846 app/data/master_rulebook.py:894
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:925
msgid ""
"(This is the section header only; the content is in the subsections "
"below.)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:255
msgid "Movement Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:258
msgid ""
"Units move from System to adjacent System (from hex to adjacent hex). The"
" distance a unit can move is determined by its level of Movement "
"technology, and is measured in hexes. Units may be moved separately or "
"together. All players start the game at Movement technology level 1. This"
" means each unit may move only one hex during the Movement Phase of each "
"turn. If a player develops their Movement technology during the Economic "
"Phase (7.5), they increase the number of hexes each ship may move in a "
"turn, as follows:\n"
"\n"
"- Level 2: 1 hex in each of the first two turns, 2 hexes in the third "
"turn.\n"
"- Level 3: 1 hex in the first turn, 2 hexes in each of the second and "
"third turns.\n"
"- Level 4: 2 hexes in all three turns.\n"
"- Level 5: 2 hexes in each of the first two turns, 3 hexes in the third "
"turn.\n"
"- Level 6: 2 hexes in the first turn, 3 hexes in each of the second and "
"third turns.\n"
"- Level 7: 3 hexes in all three turns."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:270 app/data/master_rulebook.py:419
msgid "Non-Combat Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:273
msgid ""
"Regardless of a player's Movement technology level, these ships (8.4, "
"8.5, 13.1) move only 1 hex each turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:278 app/data/master_rulebook.py:993
msgid "Decoys"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:281
msgid ""
"Decoys (8.3) always move at the speed of the current Movement technology "
"level."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:286
msgid "Non-Moving Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:289
msgid ""
"Bases (8.1), Starbases (38.5), Defense Satellite Networks (14.0), and "
"Shipyards (8.2) cannot move."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:294 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1713
msgid "Movement Restrictions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:297
msgid ""
"A unit may not enter a hex with a face down (unexplored) System marker, a"
" Nebula, or Asteroids unless it starts its turn adjacent to it and moves "
"into that hex as its first move. Also, entering a hex with any of these "
"markers ends that unit's movement, regardless of its Movement technology "
"level.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Group that could move two hexes begins the Movement Phase "
"adjacent to a hex with an Asteroids marker. It may enter the hex but must"
" stop after doing so.\n"
"\n"
"Non-combat ships (5.4) may not enter a hex with a face down (unexplored) "
"System marker, enemy unit, or enemy Colony unless a combat-capable ship "
"also enters that hex (it need not have started in the same location)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:306
msgid "Enemy-Occupied Hexes"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:309
msgid ""
"Units must immediately stop all movement when entering a hex containing "
"enemy combat capable units and attack them during the Combat Phase. If a "
"unit enters a System containing only enemy non-combat capable ships, "
"those defenseless ships are immediately destroyed and do not impede "
"movement or reveal ships (or technology; 9.10); the moving (attacking) "
"units may continue moving. Combat capable units may ignore enemy Colonies"
" on a planet and pass through the hex or stay in the hex. If a unit ends "
"its move in a hex with an enemy Colony, the unit may attack during the "
"Combat Phase (5.10)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:314
msgid "Planets & Colonization"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:317
msgid ""
"A planet without a Colony on it has no effect on movement. A non-"
"colonized planet may be colonized by a Colony Ship (8.4). A colonized "
"planet may not be colonized again until the existing Colony is destroyed "
"(5.10.3, 21.9)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:322
msgid "Initiating Colonization"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:325
msgid ""
"Place the Colony Ship (ship side up) on the planet marker. A player may "
"do this at any point during their turn if there are no non-cloaked (16.0)"
" enemy units in the same hex as the colony ship and empty planet. Once "
"colonization is announced in this way, the Colony Ship may no longer "
"move. It has begun the process of forming a Colony and has dismantled "
"itself for the raw material needed to start the process. From this point "
"on, it is considered a Colony. Colonization takes time and the Colony "
"will grow in future Economic Phases (7.7)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:330
msgid "Colonizing Barren Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:333
msgid ""
"Some planets are labeled \"Barren.\" They may not be colonized without "
"Terraforming technology (9.7). Once a Barren Planet is colonized, the "
"planet functions like any other planet. It delivers resources and grows "
"just like other planets. If a Colony on a Barren Planet is destroyed, the"
" planet immediately reverts to a Barren Planet. If playing with Alien "
"Technology cards, see 11.0."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:338
msgid "Combat Phase"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:346
msgid "Combat Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:349
msgid ""
"Combat occurs during the Combat Phase whenever opposing units (enemies) "
"are in the same hex. Combat is mandatory and takes place within a hex. "
"The units which moved into the hex and initiated combat are the "
"attackers, while the opposing units are referred to as the defenders. "
"Both the attacking and defending units may fire, often more than once, "
"and combat continues until only one side has units remaining in the hex."
"\n"
"\n"
"There is no three-way combat in this game. If a player moves into a hex "
"with units from two different sides, they may pick which one they want to"
" engage first. Only units that survive/remain in the hex may be used in "
"the second battle. Damage is removed between battles.\n"
"\n"
"If multiple combats are initiated during the same turn the active player "
"decides the order in which they are resolved."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:355
msgid ""
"PLAY NOTE: It is possible for all of one player’s units to fire before "
"their opponent has a chance to roll the dice. It is also possible for a "
"ship to be destroyed before it fires even once. Developing a higher "
"Tactics technology than your opponent can be critical."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:361
msgid "Move Units Off Map"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:364
msgid ""
"If a Decoy is present (8.3), it is eliminated before any combat takes "
"place (if a side only has Decoys, the other side doesn't have to reveal "
"their units). Take all units in the System temporarily to a convenient "
"area off the playing board. Alternatively, players may use the Battle "
"Board (37.4.2). Mark the System in which the battle takes place with the "
"Battle marker as a reminder. The attacker and defender both reveal and "
"arrange their units in \"battle lines\". Each line should be organized "
"according to Weapon Class (A-Class at one end, B-Class next to A-Class, "
"etc.)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:369
msgid "Determine Combat Screening"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:372
msgid ""
"Next, each side counts the number of combat-capable units involved in the"
" battle, including Bases (8.1), Starbases (38.5), Defense Satellite "
"Networks (14.0), and Shipyards (8.2). The side with the greater number of"
" combat-capable units has the option of Combat Screening (5.7)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:377
msgid "Determine Fleet Size Bonus"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:380
msgid ""
"If a player has twice as many unscreened, combat-capable units as their "
"opponent, their firing units enjoy a +1 bonus to their Attack Strengths. "
"Determine this Fleet Size Bonus at the start of each firing round. It is "
"possible that as a battle progresses, and units are destroyed or retreat,"
" the size differential will change, so that the side who enjoys this "
"bonus at the start of combat may lose it in a later round, and vice "
"versa. Note that the smaller side is not penalized in its fire. Mines "
"(17.1) do not count towards Fleet Size in any way. Bases, Starbases, "
"Defense Satellite Networks, and Shipyards count towards this bonus."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:385
msgid "Resolve Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:388
msgid ""
"Combat is resolved starting with the A-Class units, progressing to the "
"B-Class units, and so forth in descending order, until all units have had"
" the opportunity to fire. No unit may fire more than once in a combat "
"round but can be a target more than once."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:393
msgid "Repeat if Necessary"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:396
msgid ""
"If both the attacker and defender still have units in the hex after a "
"round of combat, perform another round of combat starting with the Combat"
" Screening step (5.7). Combat may last any number of rounds. After the "
"first round is completed a unit which has an opportunity to fire at a "
"target may retreat instead (5.9)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:401
msgid "Firing Order"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:404
msgid ""
"Combat fire is never simultaneous. A-Class units fire before B-Class "
"units, B-Class units fire before C-Class units, etc. If multiple groups "
"with the same firing class are present the Group with the highest Tactics"
" technology fires first. If the Weapon Class and Tactics technology of "
"multiple Groups are the same then the Defender's Groups fire first. If "
"the Groups belong to the same player, that player decides which of their "
"Groups fires first, but must resolve the entire fire by one Group before "
"moving to the next. If combat is taking place in a System with Asteroids "
"or a Nebula (5.8), all ships except for Boarding Ships (19.0) are "
"considered E-Class regardless of what is printed on the counters.\n"
"\n"
"PLAY NOTE: It is possible for all of one player's units to fire before "
"their opponent has a chance to roll the dice. It is also possible for a "
"ship to be destroyed before it fires even once. Developing a higher "
"Tactics technology than your opponent can be critical."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:411
msgid "Who May Fire"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:414
msgid ""
"Only combat-capable units may fire. A unit may fire at any enemy unit in "
"the same hex except units that are screened (5.7). If units are part of "
"the same Group, they may fire individually and at different targets. A "
"unit may always decide not to fire. Fighter Squadrons (15.2) may also "
"fire and they do so independently of their Carriers (15.1)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:422
msgid ""
"Decoys are eliminated before any combat takes place.\n"
"\n"
"Colony Ships, Miners, and MS Pipelines may not retreat and are "
"automatically destroyed if alone or if all accompanying friendly combat-"
"capable units are eliminated or retreat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:429
msgid "Fire Resolution"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:432
msgid ""
"Select a firing unit and a target. Add the firing unit's Attack Strength "
"to its Attack technology level (9.2). The sum is the total Attack "
"Strength.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Cruiser's Attack Strength is 4, and if it has an Attack "
"technology level of 1, the total Attack Strength is 5.\n"
"\n"
"Increase the Attack Strength by one (+1) if the Fleet Size Bonus is "
"applicable (5.1.3).\n"
"\n"
"Next, add the target's Defense Strength to its Defense technology level "
"and subtract this sum from the total Attack Strength to get the \"To "
"Hit\" number. The attacking side rolls a die for each unit in the Group "
"that is firing on the target. Dice may be rolled one at a time for each "
"unit and the result seen before deciding on the target for the next unit."
" For each die rolled, if the die roll is equal to or less than the number"
" needed to hit, a hit is scored. Regardless of the number needed to hit, "
"a roll of 1 will always score a hit.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: If a target has a Defense Strength of 1 and a Defense technology"
" level of 1, 2 is subtracted from the total Attack Strength. If the "
"Cruiser from the above example is the firing unit, it would need to roll "
"a 3 or less to score a hit.\n"
"\n"
"Important: The Attack and Defense technology modification may not "
"normally exceed a unit's Hull Size (9.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:447
msgid "Recording Hits"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:450
msgid ""
"Damage is cumulative and is recorded by placing Damage markers near the "
"Group counter during battle. When a unit receives hits equal to its Hull "
"Size, it is destroyed. Adjust the numeral marker under the Group counter "
"to reflect the loss of the unit, and if the Group only had one unit, "
"remove the Group counter.\n"
"\n"
"Two or more units in the same Group may not have damage applied to them "
"at the same time; all damage must be applied to a single unit, and only "
"after it is destroyed may subsequent damage be applied to another unit in"
" the same Group. Outside of this restriction the firing player may select"
" which unit in the group to target.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: Cruiser Group #1 has two Cruisers, which can each sustain two "
"hits before being destroyed. Therefore, at the start of combat, there is "
"a marker with a number 2 under the Group counter. During combat a hit was"
" scored on one of the Cruisers, so a 1 Damage marker is placed on top of "
"the counter to record the hit. Later, a second hit was scored on the same"
" Cruiser. The Damage marker currently marking the first hit is removed, "
"while the numeral marker underneath the Group counter is flipped to 1 to "
"show that only one Cruiser remains in the Group. If the Cruiser is later "
"destroyed, the Group counter and its numeral marker will be removed.\n"
"\n"
"Unless there are enough hits to destroy a target, hits do not affect "
"performance in any way. If otherwise able, a damaged unit may be split "
"off into a separate Group and may retreat (5.9) or be screened (5.7). At "
"the conclusion of combat, if a unit has hits but is not destroyed, the "
"hits are removed. Thus, units are considered automatically repaired after"
" combat (the turns represent a long period of time in which the crew can "
"repair the damage).\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Battleship in BB Group #2 suffers two hits in combat. After "
"the last enemy ship retreats to conclude combat, the Damage marker is "
"removed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:463
msgid "Combat Screening"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:466
msgid ""
"At the start of each firing round, if a player has more combat-capable "
"units than their opponent, they may choose to screen a number of units up"
" to the difference. Screening combat units is always voluntary.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: If the attacker has 10 combat-capable units and the defender has"
" 5, the attacker may screen as many as 5 combat-capable units."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:473
msgid "Select Units to Screen"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:476
msgid ""
"Before rolling the dice to resolve firing, set aside any units chosen to "
"be screened; they may not fire or be fired upon that round. They may "
"retreat, but only when it is their turn to do so (5.9). A combat-capable "
"unit that is screened cannot be fired on for the round even if the units "
"screening it are destroyed or retreat. Players are allowed to change the "
"composition of their screened units at the start of each round of combat "
"so that units that fired in the first round may be screened in a later "
"round and vice-versa.\n"
"\n"
"All non-combat ships (5.4) are automatically screened until the end of "
"the battle, even if the player has less combat-capable units."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:483
msgid "Exceptions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:486
msgid ""
"Players cannot screen against a Doomsday Machine (29.0) or Space Amoeba "
"(SSB 3.0/CSB 10.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:491
msgid "Special Conditions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:499
msgid "Asteroids"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:502
msgid ""
"If combat is occurring in a System with an Asteroids marker, the Attack "
"technology level of all units in the combat is considered zero, "
"regardless of the player's technology level. In addition, all units in "
"the combat are considered to be E-Class, regardless of what is printed on"
" their counters. This represents the extra protection provided by the "
"Asteroids and the difficulty involved in bringing longer ranged and more "
"advanced weapons to bear in the middle of an asteroid belt. Note that a "
"unit's base Attack Strength is unaffected."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:507
msgid "Nebulae"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:510
msgid ""
"If combat is occurring in a System with a Nebula marker, the Defense "
"technology level of all units in the combat is considered zero, "
"regardless of the player's technology level. In addition, all units in "
"the combat are considered to be E-Class, regardless of what is printed on"
" their counters. This represents the nebula wreaking havoc on the unit's "
"defensive systems. Note that a unit's base Defense Strength is "
"unaffected."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:515
msgid "Additional Effects"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:518
msgid "See Additional Terrain (25.0) for more combat effects."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:523
msgid "Retreats"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:526
msgid ""
"Retreat is a voluntary action. After the first round, a unit that can "
"move may choose to retreat instead of firing when it would be its regular"
" turn to fire. Retreat may require a player to place a new Group counter "
"on the game board (that is, if one ship in a Group retreats, leaving the "
"rest of the Group in the hex). Non-combat ships (5.4), Bases (8.1), "
"Starbases (38.5), Defense Satellite Networks (14.0), Shipyards (8.2), "
"Titans (22.0), and Missiles (24.4) may not retreat. Retreats may not be "
"conducted after all enemy space combat-capable ships have been destroyed "
"or have retreated."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:531
msgid "Retreat Location"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:534
msgid ""
"A retreating spaceship must:\n"
"- Be shifted to an adjacent System.\n"
"- The hex may not contain any enemy units\n"
"- It may not be an unexplored System or a Super Nova (6.5).\n"
"- It may retreat into a Black Hole hex (6.3) but may not use Black Hole "
"Slingshot (31.0) during the retreat.\n"
"- It must retreat into a System that is closer to one of its Colonies "
"than the hex that it is retreating from; this does not need to be the "
"closest Colony. Closeness is determined counting hexes and ignoring "
"intervening terrain and units.\n"
"- If no legal retreat exists, the ship may not retreat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:545
msgid "Colonies & Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:553 app/data/master_rulebook.py:769
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:851 app/data/master_rulebook.py:899
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:930 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1827
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2171 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3024
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:3069 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3422
msgid "Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:556
msgid ""
"A ship in a System occupied by an enemy Colony may attack the Colony only"
" after space combat is resolved in the hex. If all enemy units have "
"either been destroyed, have retreated, or decided to remain cloaked, the "
"Colony may be fired upon. Each Colony ship may only fire once at the "
"Colony per turn, and the Colony may not return fire. An attacking ship "
"may fire at a Colony only during its Combat Phase (not during the Combat "
"Phase of the Colony owner's turn). Each Colony has a Defense Strength of "
"zero and no Defense technology (but see 21.6 if playing with Ground "
"Units). Only an attacking ship's Attack Strength and Attack technology "
"are used for the purpose of determining the chance of hitting. No Fleet "
"Size Bonus (5.1.3) is applied during Colony combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:561
msgid "Effect of Hits"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:564
msgid ""
"A hit reduces the Colony one step. A Colony with 5 CP is reduced to 3 CP,"
" a 3 CP Colony is stepped down to 1 CP, and a 1 CP Colony that receives a"
" hit is removed (the planet may be colonized by another Colony Ship). A "
"newly colonized planet (the Colony Ship has been placed on the planet but"
" has not yet been flipped to the Colony side) also requires one hit to "
"destroy. If a Homeworld is hit, instead of using the 3 CP and 1 CP "
"markers, it reduces in value in increments of five. Thus, the first hit "
"reduces it to 25 CP, another hit reduces it to 20 CP, and so on. A "
"Homeworld marked with a 5 CP marker is destroyed if it takes a hit."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:569
msgid "Damaged Colonies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:572
msgid ""
"Reduced Colonies function normally. They provide CP (as indicated on the "
"marker) and grow during the Economic Phase. If reduced completely (i.e., "
"destroyed), the planet may be colonized again. If the attacking player "
"has a Colony Ship in the hex, it may immediately initiate colonization "
"(4.4)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:577
msgid "Post-Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:580
msgid ""
"Groups revealed in combat are now returned to the map but remain face up "
"and may be examined, along with their numeral markers, by other players "
"at any time. If Groups start their turn in the same hex as one of their "
"Colonies, they may be flipped face down (hiding their numeral marker "
"also) before being moved (if able) and remain that way until they once "
"again engage in combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:588
msgid ""
"Except for the players' Homeworlds, all Systems are unexplored at the "
"start of the game. This is indicated by the placement of face-down System"
" markers during setup."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:593
msgid "Exploration Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:596
msgid ""
"If a unit shares a hex with a face-down (unexplored) System marker during"
" the Exploration Phase, it must explore that System. Flip the marker over"
" and reveal its identity to all players. Apply effects immediately. "
"Cruisers can be equipped with Exploration technology (9.8), which allows "
"them to explore during the Movement Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:601
msgid "Planets, Nebulae, Asteroids"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:604
msgid ""
"These markers remain in the hex and affect future game play.\n"
"- Planets: Can be colonized (4.4)\n"
"- Nebulae, Asteroids: Affect movement (4.2) & combat (5.8)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:611
msgid "Black Holes"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:614
msgid ""
"Any ship that moves or explores into a hex containing a Black Hole must "
"momentarily pause movement to check for survival. Each ship in a Group "
"must be checked individually for survival. On a roll of 1-6 the ship "
"survives; on a roll of 7-10, it is destroyed. This die roll is made the "
"instant a ship enters a Black Hole. Ships that begin their Movement Phase"
" in a Black Hole do not have to roll again, unless they move out of the "
"Black Hole and back in. If the ship survives its encounter with the Black"
" Hole, it may continue moving (Movement technology level permitting). The"
" Black Hole remains in the hex for the rest of the game.\n"
"\n"
"Fighters (15.2) and Ground Units (21.2) do not have to roll for survival "
"when entering the hex of a Black Hole and are only eliminated if the "
"surviving ships do not have the capacity to carry them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:624
msgid ""
"Space is dangerous, especially the unexplored bits of it. When this "
"marker is revealed, all units in the hex are destroyed. The marker is "
"then removed from play. The hex remains empty."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:632
msgid ""
"A Super Nova dominates this sector of space. A unit revealing the Super "
"Nova must immediately retreat to the hex it just left. The Super Nova "
"remains in the hex for the rest of the game. No unit may move or retreat "
"into this System."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:640
msgid ""
"When a unit reveals this marker, the player to the right of the revealing"
" player immediately shifts the unit one hex in any direction. If more "
"than one unit is in the hex, all the units present must be shifted "
"together as a stack. If units are placed in a hex with an unrevealed "
"System marker, that marker must immediately be explored. After shifting "
"units out of the hex, the Lost in Space marker is removed, and the hex "
"remains empty."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:645 app/data/master_rulebook.py:4142
msgid "Minerals"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:648
msgid "Precious resources vital to industry."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:653 app/data/master_rulebook.py:685
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1009 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1509
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1533 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1947
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2485 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2603
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2737 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2826
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:3358
msgid "Characteristics"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:656
msgid ""
"This marker has no effect on movement or combat and remains in the hex "
"until towed away by a Mining Ship (8.5). Minerals may not be voluntarily "
"destroyed. If towed to a Colony or Homeworld, the Mineral marker is "
"removed from the game in the Economic Phase and generates a one-time CP "
"bonus equal to the value printed on the marker (7.2) as long as the "
"Colony or Homeworld is not blockaded (7.1.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:661
msgid "Towing Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:664
msgid ""
"Only a Mining Ship may tow a Mineral marker. A Mining Ship may only carry"
" one Mineral marker at a time. To signify towing, place the marker on top"
" of the ship towing it; the marker moves with the Mining Ship. There is "
"no cost to do this, and it may be done at any time. When the ship and its"
" Mineral marker reach a Homeworld or Colony (even a new one), the Mineral"
" may be deposited on the planet where it will remain until the Economic "
"Phase. Any number of Mineral markers may be deposited on the same "
"colonized planet. A Mineral marker, once towed by a Mining Ship, will "
"leave a hex empty. A Mining Ship may not dump its cargo in space in order"
" to pick up a better Mineral or a Space Wreck."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:669 app/data/master_rulebook.py:695
msgid "Destroyed"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:672
msgid ""
"If a Mining Ship is destroyed while towing a Mineral marker, the Mineral "
"is destroyed as well. Likewise, if a Colony with a Mineral marker is "
"destroyed or captured, the Mineral marker is also destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:680
msgid "A derelict spacecraft from an advanced civilization."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:688
msgid ""
"A Space Wreck may be towed to a Homeworld or Colony (even a new one) by a"
" Mining Ship just as if it were a Mineral marker (6.7.2). Instead of a CP"
" bonus, it earns the player a free technology upgrade during the Economic"
" Phase (7.2). To determine which technology is upgraded, roll a die and "
"consult the Space Wreck Technology table on page 48.\n"
"\n"
"If the technology rolled by the player is already at the maximum level in"
" that category, the upgrade is wasted. Regardless of the result, remove "
"the Space Wreck from the game at the end of the Economic Phase. Space "
"Wrecks may not be voluntarily destroyed. A Mining Ship may not dump a "
"Space Wreck in space in order to pick up a Mineral marker."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:698
msgid ""
"If a Mining Ship is destroyed while towing a Space Wreck marker, the "
"Space Wreck is destroyed as well. Likewise, if a Colony with a Space "
"Wreck marker is destroyed or captured, the Space Wreck marker is also "
"destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:703
msgid "Other Deep Space Discoveries"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:706
msgid ""
"Additional Terrain (25.0) and Optional Deep Space Discoveries (28.0) add "
"variety to Deep Space exploration. If not playing with a particular "
"Terrain type, remove them before set up or, when its marker is flipped, "
"remove the marker from play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:711
msgid "Using the Terrain Tiles"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:714
msgid ""
"When a permanent terrain is revealed during exploration, replace that "
"counter with the appropriate terrain tile."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:719
msgid "Home System Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:722
msgid ""
"While Home System planets are permanent terrain, they are only replaced "
"by the terrain tile once a Colony is started on them. This is because "
"these tiles have a 5 CP/Full Colony counter printed on them. Once a "
"Colony is placed, the Colony growth counter will be placed over the Full "
"counter. If the Colony is subsequently destroyed, replace the terrain "
"tile with the original System marker. If a player colonizes a planet in "
"the home space of another player, place that player's Colony marker over "
"the artwork on the tile. The exception to this is the Barren Planet in "
"each Home System, which sometimes never gets colonized; this tile has an "
"uncolonized side."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:727
msgid "Asteroids and Planet Destruction"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:730
msgid ""
"Asteroids are on the back of most planet tiles in case the planet gets "
"destroyed by a Titan (22.3)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:735
msgid "Epic Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:738
msgid ""
"Most non-planet tiles have empty space on the back. Twelve of them would "
"be needed to connect two Space Empires boards together for Epic Scenarios"
" (CSB 8.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:743
msgid "Economic Phase"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:746
msgid ""
"The Economic Phase takes place at the end of every third turn. This phase"
" consists of a sequence of tasks that the players perform secretly and "
"simultaneously:\n"
"\n"
"- Collect Colony Income (7.1)\n"
"- Collect Mineral Income (7.2)\n"
"- Pay Maintenance Costs (7.3)\n"
"- Bid to determine player order (7.4)\n"
"- Purchase units and technology (7.5)\n"
"- Place purchased units at allowable Colonies (7.6)\n"
"- Adjust Colony counters to reflect growth (7.7)\n"
"\n"
"A Production Sheet has been provided which lists these specific steps "
"with room to record the Construction Points (CP) produced and spent on "
"each item."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:761
msgid "Collect Colony Income"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:772
msgid ""
"First, each player that has more than 30 CP must discard down to 30 CP. "
"Then, the players collect income. Each Colony counter is printed with a "
"number which represents its value in CP. Players begin the Economic Phase"
" by adding the CP of all their Colonies and noting this sum on their "
"Production Sheets as income.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A player has colonized two worlds besides their Homeworld. They "
"earn 30 CP for their Homeworld and 5 CP for each of the other two worlds "
"for a total of 40 CP.\n"
"\n"
"A Colony Ship is worth 0 CP and will remain valueless until it is flipped"
" to its \"Colony\" side (7.7)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:781
msgid "Blockade Effects"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:784
msgid ""
"A Colony that has an enemy unit in the same hex (and no friendly units in"
" the case of an enemy Raider, 16.0) does not produce income but does grow"
" normally (7.7). Facilities (36.0) will also not produce income. Only "
"units with an Attack Strength may blockade a Colony."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:789
msgid "Collect Mineral Income"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:792
msgid ""
"Players add the value of all Mineral markers transported by Mining Ships "
"to their non-blockaded Colonies since the last Economic Phase (6.7.2) and"
" record the sum of these Mineral markers on their Production Sheets. The "
"Mineral markers are then removed from the game. This is a one-time "
"income. If a player has salvaged a Space Wreck (6.8), they roll for the "
"technology upgrade now. If a Colony is blockaded (7.1.2), the benefit "
"from Minerals and Space Wrecks on the planet cannot be collected until "
"the blockade is lifted."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:797
msgid "Pay Maintenance Costs"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:805
msgid "Maintenance Cost"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:808
msgid ""
"All units except those noted below have a maintenance cost equal to their"
" Hull Size. Players add up the Hull Size of all these units and note the "
"sum on their Production Sheet, subtracting this maintenance cost from "
"their income. If the total maintenance cost exceeds a player's income, "
"the player's net income is zero.\n"
"\n"
"Bases, Starbases, Defense Satellite Networks, Colonies, Colony Ships, "
"Mines, Mining Ships, MS Pipelines, and Shipyards do not incur maintenance"
" costs.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Cruiser Group has 3 ships in it. Each Cruiser has a "
"maintenance cost of 2 CP (Hull Size of 2), so the Group costs 6 CP to "
"maintain. The player subtracts that from their income and notes the "
"remainder on their Production Sheet."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:817
msgid "Scuttling Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:820
msgid ""
"A player may scuttle any of their units currently on the board, thus "
"removing the units from play (scuttled ships may be constructed anew and "
"thus returned to play). One motive for doing so is to avoid paying "
"maintenance costs. Another is to free up group counters for newer and "
"more technologically advanced spaceships.\n"
"\n"
"A unit can be scuttled at the following times:\n"
"- An Economic Phase.\n"
"- A player's own Movement Phase.\n"
"- Another player's Movement Phase the moment they enter the hex that the "
"counter is in (treating it like a Decoy; 8.3).\n"
"- Combat Phase – only to free up a counter to allow a ship to be "
"screened.\n"
"- During a retreat.\n"
"- Because of any of the following Resource Cards (39.0): Self-Destruct, "
"Heroic Ship, Overload Weapons, Forced System Shutdown, or Play Dead."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:833
msgid "Bid to Determine Player Order"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:836
msgid ""
"This abstractly represents resources, supplies, intelligence, and capital"
" spent to speed production schedules, etc.\n"
"\n"
"Players enter a number of CP as a bid on their Production Sheets. The "
"highest bid will earn the privilege of determining the player order for "
"the next turn. This bid is optional; players may bid zero CP. Likewise, "
"there is no upper limit (except the total CP a player has available). The"
" winner of this bid chooses which player will go first, with the turn "
"order rotating clockwise around the table after that. This order stays in"
" effect until the next Economic Phase. Regardless of who wins the bid, "
"all players subtract their bid from their available CP. In the event of a"
" tie (even a tie where all players bid 0), the player who was first in "
"player order this turn (among the tied players) wins the bid. Bids are "
"revealed after the Economic Phase. On the first turn of a game, the "
"players randomly determine turn order."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:843
msgid "Purchase Units & Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:854
msgid ""
"Players may now spend CP to purchase new technology levels and ships. "
"Technology costs are listed in the Technology Progression section of the "
"Production Sheet and on the Research Chart. Ship building costs are "
"listed on the Ship Chart. Players record each purchase on their "
"Production Sheets. If a player concludes this phase with unspent CP, it "
"is carried over to the next turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:859
msgid "Carry-Over Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:862
msgid ""
"Players can only carry over 30 CP to the next Economic Phase. If playing "
"with Facilities (36.0), this limit includes any CP produced by Industrial"
" Centers. If a player saves more than 30 CP in order to refit ships "
"(9.11.3) and the refits do not take place, that player loses the excess "
"before the start of the next Economic Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:867
msgid "Initial Build Limits"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:870
msgid ""
"The starting technology levels only allow a player to build Scouts, "
"Colony Ships, Mining Ships, Decoys, Shipyards and MS Pipelines. Other "
"types of ships can only be built when a player's technology level is "
"sufficiently advanced (9.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:875
msgid "Ship Technology Level"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:878
msgid ""
"When a ship is purchased, it is automatically \"built\" with an empire's "
"latest technology. If a technology level and a spaceship are both "
"purchased in the same Economic Phase, the new technology level applies to"
" the new ship. However, ships already in play are not automatically "
"upgraded. Players may choose to build a ship with lower technology levels"
" than they are capable of building. The Ship Technology Sheet (on the "
"back of the Production Sheet) is used to keep track of each Group's "
"technology levels (9.11.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:883
msgid "Purchase Limits"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:886
msgid ""
"If all Group counters of a particular ship type are already in play, new "
"ships of that type cannot be built (unless a player scuttles ships; "
"7.3.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:891
msgid "Place Purchased Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:902
msgid ""
"Purchased units are placed at Shipyards (SY). At Shipyard technology "
"level 1, a single ship with a Hull Size of x1 may be placed per Shipyard."
" If two Shipyards with Shipyard technology level 1 occupy the same "
"System, two Hull Points (2.3.5) worth of ships may be placed there "
"(either one x2 or two x1s). There is no limit to the number of Shipyards "
"that may occupy a System. A player must have adequate Shipyard capacity "
"to build any given ship. Shipyard capacity can be increased by developing"
" Shipyard technology (9.6). New ships may be added to existing Groups in "
"the same hex if they are of the same type and technology level.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: If a player has two Shipyards and has researched Shipyard "
"technology level 1, they may only place two DD's there, or two Colony "
"Ships, or two Mines, or one CA, or one Fighter and one Mine, or any other"
" appropriate combination."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:909
msgid "Hidden Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:912
msgid ""
"Combat units are placed face down when built and remain that way until "
"combat occurs (5.0).\n"
"\n"
"DESIGN NOTE: Other players will see you manipulate the counters, but you "
"do not have to announce what you are building or scrapping."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:916
msgid ""
"DESIGN NOTE: Other players will see you manipulate the counters, but you "
"do not have to announce what you are building or scrapping."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:922
msgid "Adjust Colony Income"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:933
msgid ""
"A Colony must grow in order to reach its full capacity. At this point in "
"the Economic Phase, all Colonies are adjusted upwards to reflect this "
"development. Colonies producing 3 CP have their \"3 Colony\" counter "
"removed to reveal the 5 CP on the Colony (the maximum size). Next, "
"Colonies producing 1 CP have the \"1 Colony\" flipped to a \"3 Colony\". "
"Finally, Colony Ships on planets are flipped to their Colony side and a "
"\"1 Colony\" marker is placed on them.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: During movement, a player colonizes a planet by placing their "
"Colony Ship on top of the planet. During the subsequent Economic Phase, "
"that planet delivers no CP, but the counter is flipped to its Colony "
"side. In the next Economic Phase, that Colony would be worth 1 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:940
msgid "Damaged Homeworlds"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:943
msgid ""
"During the Economic Phase, a damaged Homeworld (5.10.2) grows one step. "
"Thus, a Homeworld marked with a 5 CP would be replaced by a 10 CP, etc."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:948
msgid "Maintenance Increase & Decrease"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:951
msgid ""
"There is a spot on the Production Sheet to track additional (future) "
"maintenance costs from purchases during this Economic Phase as well as to"
" track maintenance reductions from the loss of ships in between Economic "
"Phases. This is only an aid so that players do not have to count their "
"maintenance costs during every Economic Phase.\n"
"===\n"
"\n"
"Voila l'intégralité des sections numérotées de 1.0 à 7.8 (pages 2 à 11). "
"J'ai aussi inclus le début de la section 8.0 qui apparaît en page 11, "
"mais je me suis arrêté là puisque tu as demandé les sections 1.0 à 7.0 "
"(avec leurs sous-sections).\n"
"\n"
"Points à noter :\n"
"- La page 2 est la table des matières, sans section numérotée à "
"transcrire en tant que telle.\n"
"- Certaines sections \"parents\" (5.0, 5.8, 5.10, 7.1, 7.3, 7.5, 7.6, "
"7.7) sont des en-têtes sans texte propre au-delà de leur titre -- le "
"contenu est dans leurs sous-sections.\n"
"- Les Play Notes et Design Notes ont été inclus dans la section où ils "
"apparaissent (ex: Play Note dans 5.2, Design Note dans 7.6.2).\n"
"Voici l'extraction complète des sections 8.0 à 18.0 (pages 11-19)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:965
msgid "Basic Unit Types"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:973
msgid "Bases"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:976
msgid ""
"A player must have researched Ship Size 2 to build Bases. Like other "
"Groups, a Base is built face down with a numeral marker below it. Unlike "
"other Groups, a Base may be built at any Colony that produced income (not"
" new or blockaded Colonies) in the Economic Phase. Bases are not built by"
" Shipyards. Only one Base may be built in a single hex, and no hex may "
"have more than one Base. Once in play, a Base may not move. A Base "
"participates in combat like other Groups, except that it may not retreat."
" Bases do not incur maintenance costs. A Colony may build both a Base and"
" a Shipyard in the same Econ Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:981
msgid "Shipyards (SY)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:984
msgid ""
"Shipyards represent the facilities and infrastructure necessary for the "
"construction of spaceships.\n"
"\n"
"Newly constructed units enter play in a hex with a Shipyard, and in some "
"cases more than one Shipyard or better Shipyard Technology are needed to "
"build a single ship (9.6). Shipyards do not incur maintenance costs.\n"
"\n"
"Shipyards may only be built at Colonies that produced income (not new or "
"blockaded Colonies) in the Economic Phase. A Colony may build both a "
"Shipyard and a Base in the same Economic Phase. Shipyards may be "
"purchased and placed at multiple planets, but no more than one per "
"planet. Additional Shipyards may be purchased at those planets in future "
"Economic Phases. Like other Groups, Shipyards are built face down with a "
"numeral marker below them. Unlike other Groups, Shipyards are produced by"
" the Colony itself and therefore do not require other Shipyards to build "
"them. Since Shipyards are placed at the same time as other units, they "
"may not be used to build ships the turn they are built."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1001 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3730
msgid "Purpose"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1004
msgid ""
"Decoys are expendable, unarmed ships that are designed to fool opponents "
"into thinking they are larger ships or an entire Group. They move about "
"just like other Groups, and a numeral marker is placed under the Decoy to"
" facilitate the ruse. The numeral marker placed under a Decoy must match "
"the CP that was paid for the Decoy(s) to indicate how many Decoys are "
"present in the Group."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1012
msgid ""
"Decoys may not explore. Decoys move at the speed of the current Movement "
"technology level (4.1) and their Movement technology level is "
"automatically upgraded. They are not capable of attacking or defending. "
"If alone in a hex entered by another player's Group, the Decoy is "
"revealed and removed immediately from play (the attacking Group is not "
"revealed in this case). If Decoys are in a hex with a friendly Group that"
" is attacked, the Decoys are automatically eliminated at the start of "
"combat (5.4)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1017
msgid "Purchasing and Maintenance"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1020
msgid ""
"Decoys may only be built at Colonies that produced income (not new or "
"blockaded Colonies) in the Economic Phase. The cost is 1 CP, and do not "
"require a Shipyard to be constructed. Decoys do not incur maintenance "
"cost."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1025
msgid "Colony Ships & Colonies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1028
msgid ""
"Colony Ship counters represent either a ship or a Colony (when on a "
"planet). When a Colony Ship colonizes a planet (4.4) it will be flipped "
"from its ship side to its Colony side in the ensuing Economic Phase. "
"Barren Planets may not be colonized unless Terraforming technology has "
"been developed (9.7). The movement rate of a Colony Ship is one hex, "
"regardless of a player's Movement technology level. Colony Ships always "
"represent a single ship and never have a numeral marker underneath them. "
"Colony Ships are always placed face up."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1033
msgid "Mining Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1036
msgid ""
"Mining Ships are used for towing Mineral markers (6.7) or Space Wrecks "
"(6.8). The movement rate of a Mining Ship is one hex, regardless of a "
"player's Movement technology level. Mining Ships always represent a "
"single ship and never have a numeral marker underneath them. Mining Ships"
" do not incur a maintenance cost. The 5 on the back of the Mining Ship "
"counter is only relevant when using the Terraforming Nebulae optional "
"rule; 34.0)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1041
msgid "Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1049
msgid "Purchasing Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1052
msgid ""
"Players may spend CP to improve their technologies. Technologies are "
"purchased in \"levels,\" with each level costing CP as indicated on the "
"Research Chart. When a technology level is purchased, the appropriate "
"number on the Technology Progression section of the Production Sheet is "
"circled. Levels must be purchased in numerical order and only one level "
"of technology may be purchased in each category per Economic Phase "
"(although a player may purchase levels in two or more Technologies "
"simultaneously).\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: Attack technology level 2 must be purchased before Attack "
"technology level 3; and Attack technology 2 and 3 may not be purchased in"
" the same Economic Phase.\n"
"\n"
"Several technologies have had their costs adjusted since the initial "
"release of Space Empires. These new costs should be used at all times – "
"even if playing with only the base game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1061
msgid "Attack & Defense Technologies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1064
msgid ""
"Improvement in these technology levels add to the combat capabilities of "
"a player's ships (5.5). Note that ships can never carry an Attack or "
"Defense technology level greater than their Hull Size (9.4). These are "
"the only technologies that are limited by Hull Size.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: Scouts, Destroyers and Shipyards can never have an Attack "
"technology greater than level 1, even if that player has purchased a "
"higher Attack technology level."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1068
msgid ""
"Important: The Attack and Defense technology modification may not "
"normally exceed a unit’s Hull Size (9.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1074
msgid "Tactics Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1077
msgid ""
"This technology affects which ships fire first in combat when they have "
"the same Weapon Class (5.2). This abstractly represents not only the "
"tactical training of a player's units, but also certain aspects of "
"technology. Tactics technology is not limited by Hull Size. Like other "
"technologies, the Tactics level is specific to a Group."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1082
msgid "Ship Size Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1085
msgid ""
"Increasing this technology allows the purchase of larger ships. The Hull "
"Size shown on a unit's counter indicates how many Hull Points are "
"required to build it. The Research Chart shows which ships can be "
"purchased at each technology level. This tech may be used in the same "
"Econ Phase it is purchased.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A player just purchased Ship Size level 3. That same Economic "
"Phase they may purchase Cruisers (CA)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1092
msgid "Movement Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1095
msgid ""
"This represents how fast a ship may move (4.1). Reaction Movement also "
"comes with some levels of Movement technology when using that optional "
"rule (35.0). See the Movement Technology Chart near the back of this "
"book."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1100
msgid "Shipyard Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1103
msgid ""
"Each player starts with a Shipyard technology level of 1, which can "
"produce 1 Hull Point of ships each Economic Phase. At technology level 2,"
" each Shipyard produces 1.5 Hull Points (rounded down). At technology "
"level 3, each Shipyard produces 2 Hull Points each.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: a player has developed Shipyard technology level 2, and they "
"have two Shipyards in the same hex. Those Shipyards may now build a total"
" of 3 Hull Points worth of ships each Economic Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1110
msgid "Terraforming Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1113
msgid ""
"After purchasing Terraforming 1, a player's Colony Ships may colonize "
"Barren Planets (4.4.2). Colony Ships that were purchased before this "
"technology do not gain this benefit.\n"
"\n"
"Terraforming 2 is only relevant when using the Terraforming Nebulae "
"Optional rule (34.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1120
msgid "Exploration 1 Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1123
msgid ""
"This technology greatly improves the sensors and other equipment needed "
"for exploration. Only Cruisers, Flagships, Replicator Exploration Ships "
"(40.7.4) may be equipped with it. During the Movement Phase, each ship so"
" equipped may peek at one adjacent face-down (unexplored) System marker "
"before moving. The player has the choice of returning the marker face "
"down or revealing the marker. If the marker is revealed and it is a "
"marker with a one-time effect (e.g., Danger!, etc.), it is removed. "
"Whether the marker is revealed or not, any negative effects from flipping"
" that marker do not affect the exploring ship.\n"
"\n"
"The ship is also allowed to move normally in that Movement Phase (and may"
" explore a different hex in the usual fashion, as per 6.1). A ship that "
"uses Exploration 1 technology is not revealed. Exploration technology "
"cannot be used on a hex that has a Doomsday Machine or Alien Player fleet"
" (SSB 4.0) in it.\n"
"\n"
"PLAY NOTE: This means that a ship equipped with Exploration 1 technology "
"can explore 2 hexes each turn (one with Exploration technology and one by"
" moving into the hex).\n"
"\n"
"An advanced version of this technology (Reaction Movement, 35.0) is "
"available as an optional rule."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1134
msgid "Fast Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1137
msgid ""
"Some ships can be equipped with Fast technology, giving them greater "
"mobility. Such ships may move one extra space on turn 1 (only). All other"
" normal movement rules apply."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1142
msgid "Fast 1 (formerly called Fast Battlecruisers or Fast BC)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1145
msgid ""
"Allows Battlecruisers, Flagships (23.0), and Unique Ships (41.0) to be "
"equipped with Fast technology. All Space Pirates (25.7) are equipped with"
" Fast 1, regardless of whether it is researched.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: If a player has Fast BC 1 and Movement 4, their other ships may "
"move 2 hexes each turn. Their BCs will be able to move 3 hexes on turn 1."
"\n"
"\n"
"Once this technology has been researched, Decoys may also use it just "
"like they can use other Movement technology. Players do not need to "
"research Ship Size 4 before researching this technology."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1154
msgid "Fast 2"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1157
msgid ""
"Fast 2 costs 10 CP and is only available when using Advanced Construction"
" (38.0). This technology allows DestroyerXs, Battle Carriers, and "
"RaiderXs to be equipped with Fast technology."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1162
msgid "Revealing Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1165
msgid ""
"The technology present on any ships in a battle is revealed at the start "
"of combat if combat-capable units are involved on both sides, though "
"Movement technology is also revealed in the Movement Phase in which it is"
" used. Technology is revealed before Mines are resolved (17.0). Ground "
"Combat 2, Terraforming 1-2, and Military Academy 1 are not revealed in "
"space combat. All other technologies are revealed.\n"
"\n"
"To reveal a technology a player just announces it. They do not have to "
"show their Production Sheet until the end of the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1169
msgid ""
"PLAY NOTE: For those who wish to avoid the bookkeeping required by this "
"rule, the Instant Technology Upgrade optional rule removes it (30.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1175
msgid "New Technology Levels"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1178
msgid ""
"Technologies apply to ships purchased in the same and subsequent Economic"
" Phases. Thus, if a player purchases Attack 2 in the same turn that they "
"purchase a Battleship, this new Battleship is \"equipped\" with Attack 2;"
" however, ships purchased in previous turns are not equipped with it. "
"Players may choose to build a ship with lower technology levels than they"
" are capable of building."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1183
msgid "Group Uniformity"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1186
msgid ""
"Spaceships in the same Group must have identical technology (such as "
"Attack level, Tactics level, and so forth). If a player has two "
"spaceships of the same type but with different technology capabilities, "
"they must be represented by different Group counters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1191
msgid "Record-Keeping"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1194
msgid ""
"Players keep track of a Group's technology levels on the Ship Technology "
"Sheet using each Group's identification number. When a player purchases a"
" ship, they circle the current technologies on the row corresponding to "
"its Group on the sheet. There is no need to ever erase the circles on the"
" sheet since a player's technology level never decreases.\n"
"\n"
"To save space, the Ship Technology Sheet does not list the technologies "
"that a ship must have. For example, Attack 0, Tactics 0, and Move 1 are "
"not listed on the sheet. All ships must at least have those levels of "
"technology. Attack 1 is the first Attack technology listed. If Attack 1 "
"is not circled, then the ship must still be at Attack 0. Likewise, for "
"Fighters, Fighter 1 technology is not listed because the Fighter must "
"obviously be at least at Fighter 1."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1198
msgid ""
"PLAY NOTE: This means that a ship equipped with Exploration 1 technology "
"can explore 2 hexes each turn (one with Exploration technology and one by"
" moving into the hex)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1204
msgid "Refits"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1207
msgid ""
"A ship may be upgraded to a player's current technology level. The ship "
"must be in a System with a Shipyard. There is no limit to the number of "
"ships that can be upgraded at a single Shipyard. The ship must not move "
"or use Exploration Tech for an entire turn (it must begin and end the "
"turn at the Shipyard), and a number of CP must be expended equal to its "
"Hull Size. This upgrades all its technologies to the current level.\n"
"\n"
"Normally this means that a player must have CP left over from the "
"previous Economic Phase in order to upgrade ships (7.5.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1214
msgid "Automatic Upgrades"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1217
msgid ""
"Bases, Starbases, Defense Satellite Networks, and Shipyards are "
"automatically and instantly upgraded to the latest technology levels "
"without cost (limited to their Hull Size). Shipyards may even use a new "
"level of Shipyard technology that was just purchased.\n"
"\n"
"PLAY NOTE: For those who wish to avoid the bookkeeping required by this "
"rule, the Instant Technology Upgrade optional rule removes it (30.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1224
msgid "Empire Advantages"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1232
msgid "Random Method"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1235
msgid ""
"Each player is dealt two Empire Advantage cards at the start of the game."
" A player using Replicators (40.0) is dealt two Replicator Empire "
"Advantage Cards instead. Players choose one and discard the other face "
"down."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1240
msgid "Balanced Method"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1243
msgid ""
"This method cannot be used when any Player is using Replicators. One more"
" Empire Advantage card than the number of players is dealt face up in the"
" middle of the table. Each player begins the game with 75 CP. Open CP "
"bidding begins for choice of an Empire Advantage until no one is willing "
"to beat the highest bid. The winner of the bid subtracts their bid amount"
" from their starting CP and picks an Empire Advantage. Those who do not "
"win the bid lose nothing.\n"
"\n"
"The remaining players repeat the process and bid for choice of the next "
"Empire Advantage. When only one player is left, they bid zero, choose one"
" of the two remaining Empire Advantages, and discard the other.\n"
"\n"
"In the unlikely event that someone bids more than 75 CP (or more than the"
" amount agreed upon), then any additional CP is subtracted from their "
"future income. In this case, maintenance would have to be paid, with any "
"income going to pay off their original bid."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1252
msgid "Revealing Empire Advantage Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1255
msgid ""
"Empire Advantage cards are placed face down in front of each player. When"
" their reveal condition is met, they are turned face up and left that way"
" for the remainder of the game. A player's card is also revealed if "
"Ground Units capture one of their Colonies (21.13). Consult the Expanded "
"Sequence of Play in the Competitive Scenario Book (CSB) for information "
"on when these cards are revealed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1260 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3869
msgid "Special Considerations"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1263
msgid ""
"See the Card Manifest for the complete list of Empire Advantages and "
"additional details that don't fit on the cards.\n"
"\n"
"In addition, do not use an advantage if not playing with a rule that it "
"modifies. For example, if playing with the Instant Upgrade rule (30.0), "
"don't play with Nano-technology.\n"
"\n"
"And We Still Carry Swords should not be used when playing the Planetary "
"Gate Scenario (too powerful)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1272
msgid "Captured Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1275
msgid ""
"Empire Advantages are never gained from a player when their planet is "
"captured."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1280 app/data/master_rulebook.py:1853
msgid "Captured Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1283
msgid ""
"Unless otherwise noted, ships captured through boarding (19.3) do not "
"retain their Empire Advantage."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1288
msgid "Scenario Restrictions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1291
msgid ""
"When playing any scenario that at any point has only two hexes of Deep "
"Space between player's home areas, do not use the following Empire "
"Advantages: Ancient Race, Giant Race, House of Speed, On the Move, "
"Industrious Race, Longbowmen"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1304
msgid "Acquiring Alien Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1307
msgid ""
"Before the start of the game the Alien Technology deck is shuffled and "
"placed face down next to the game board. Before shuffling, the players "
"should remove any cards from the deck that only modify rules not being "
"used in the game.\n"
"\n"
"When a Barren Planet in the Deep Space portion of the map is initially "
"colonized (4.4.2) or captured (21.13), the player may draw two of these "
"cards. If a drawn card does not apply to the empire you are playing, it "
"may be revealed and discarded for a different one. They secretly choose "
"one card and discard the other face down. The player must pay 10 CP "
"during the next Economic Phase to keep the chosen card, otherwise it must"
" be discarded. This expenditure is recorded under ship purchases on the "
"Production Sheet.\n"
"\n"
"If playing with Non-Player Aliens (18.0), there is no cost for the chosen"
" card.\n"
"\n"
"An Alien Technology card is not drawn for a planet that has been "
"previously colonized or captured by any player.\n"
"\n"
"The only player who may benefit from an Alien Technology card is the "
"player who drew it. An Alien Technology card may not be gained by "
"scrapping a captured ship (19.5.1) that is benefitting from it or by "
"capturing an enemy planet. Alien Technology cards only start granting "
"their benefit after the current player's turn.\n"
"\n"
"Cards that can benefit ships already built (like Holodeck) do so "
"immediately (all existing ships get that benefit). This alien technology "
"is so advanced that it is easy to install.\n"
"\n"
"Ships that are captured do still retain the benefit of the Alien "
"Technology card. There is just no way for the capturing player to gain "
"the ability from the ship and duplicate it for their other ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1324
msgid "Revealing Alien Technology Levels"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1327
msgid ""
"Alien Technology cards are placed face down in front of their owner. When"
" their reveal condition is met, they are turned face up and left that way"
" for the remainder of the game. A player's Alien Technology cards are "
"also revealed if Ground Units capture one of their Colonies (21.13) or if"
" a ship benefitting from it is captured. Consult the Expanded Sequence of"
" Play in the Competitive Scenario Book (CSB) for information on when "
"these cards are revealed. See the Card Manifest for a complete list of "
"Alien Technology cards."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1335
msgid ""
"Crew Cards provide many unique combinations with which to diversify ship "
"Groups and add tactical nuance to a player's fleets. Crew Cards can be "
"used in addition or separately from Experience (37.0). If used together, "
"any bonuses of Crew Cards and Experience are cumulative. See the Card "
"Manifest for a complete list of Crew Cards."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1337
msgid ""
"12.0 Crew Cards Crew Cards provide many unique combinations with which to"
" diversify ship Groups and add tactical nuance to a player’s fleets. Crew"
" Cards can be used in addition or separately from Experience (37.0). If "
"used together, any bonuses of Crew Cards and Experience are cumulative. "
"See the Card Manifest for a complete list of Crew Cards. 12.1 ACQUIRING "
"CREW CARDS Before the start of the game, separately shuffle the Crew "
"Cards and Replicator Crew Cards (if playing with them) into face-down "
"piles next to the game board. During every even-numbered Economic Phase "
"(2, 4, 6, etc.) each player draws two Crew Cards from the appropriate "
"deck, chooses one to keep face down, and discards the other. Discarded "
"Crew Cards are always separated by type and placed face down and “messy” "
"so they are not mistaken for a draw pile. Reshuffle a discard pile when "
"its deck has run out of cards. Each player is limited to 5 Crew Cards at "
"a time. If a player already has 5 Crew Cards in play, cards may be drawn "
"normally, but an exist- ing card must be discarded to keep one of the new"
" ones. 12.2 UTILIZING CREW CARDS 12.2.1 Assigning Crew Cards: Crew Cards "
"must be assigned during the same Economic Phase during which they are "
"drawn. They can be assigned to a Group in the player’s Home System or a "
"Group the player builds during the same Economic Phase (even if built "
"outside of the Home System). A Crew Card that cannot be assigned must be "
"discarded. Assigned Crew Cards remain face down in front of the player. "
"Group assignments can be tracked by writing the number of the Crew Card "
"by the Group on the Ship Technology Sheet. Alternatively, a dry erase "
"marker can be used to write the Group on the Crew Card. Crew Cards are "
"turned face up when their ability is used or when their Group is "
"revealed. A Crew Card used outside of combat must be revealed, but its "
"Group is not revealed. Once turned face up, they remain face up for the "
"rest of the game. Ships may join or leave a Group with a Crew Card, but "
"the Crew Card must stay with the same Group until that Group is "
"destroyed. The only exception is if two Groups combine, each with one "
"Crew Card, both Crew Cards may be kept by the newly combined Group. "
"12.2.2 Replicator Crew Cards: These represent part of the AI that have "
"formed distinct personalities. All the rules for normal Crew Cards apply "
"to Replicator Crew Cards. Each Replicator Crew has three numeral counters"
" (1/2, 3/4, and 5/6) with its name on it. These may be used in place of "
"normal numeral markers to indicate which Group that Crew is assigned to. "
"Replicators can only have one Crew on a Group."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1343
msgid "Acquiring Crew Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1346
msgid ""
"Before the start of the game, separately shuffle the Crew Cards and "
"Replicator Crew Cards (if playing with them) into face-down piles next to"
" the game board.\n"
"\n"
"During every even-numbered Economic Phase (2, 4, 6, etc.) each player "
"draws two Crew Cards from the appropriate deck, chooses one to keep face "
"down, and discards the other. Discarded Crew Cards are always separated "
"by type and placed face down and \"messy\" so they are not mistaken for a"
" draw pile. Reshuffle a discard pile when its deck has run out of cards. "
"Each player is limited to 5 Crew Cards at a time. If a player already has"
" 5 Crew Cards in play, cards may be drawn normally, but an existing card "
"must be discarded to keep one of the new ones."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1353
msgid "Utilizing Crew Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1361
msgid "Assigning Crew Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1364
msgid ""
"Crew Cards must be assigned during the same Economic Phase during which "
"they are drawn. They can be assigned to a Group in the player's Home "
"System or a Group the player builds during the same Economic Phase (even "
"if built outside of the Home System). A Crew Card that cannot be assigned"
" must be discarded.\n"
"\n"
"Assigned Crew Cards remain face down in front of the player. Group "
"assignments can be tracked by writing the number of the Crew Card by the "
"Group on the Ship Technology Sheet. Alternatively, a dry erase marker can"
" be used to write the Group on the Crew Card.\n"
"\n"
"Crew Cards are turned face up when their ability is used or when their "
"Group is revealed. A Crew Card used outside of combat must be revealed, "
"but its Group is not revealed. Once turned face up, they remain face up "
"for the rest of the game.\n"
"\n"
"Ships may join or leave a Group with a Crew Card, but the Crew Card must "
"stay with the same Group until that Group is destroyed. The only "
"exception is if two Groups combine, each with one Crew Card, both Crew "
"Cards may be kept by the newly combined Group."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1375
msgid "Replicator Crew Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1378
msgid ""
"These represent part of the AI that have formed distinct personalities. "
"All the rules for normal Crew Cards apply to Replicator Crew Cards. Each "
"Replicator Crew has three numeral counters (1/2, 3/4, and 5/6) with its "
"name on it. These may be used in place of normal numeral markers to "
"indicate which Group that Crew is assigned to. Replicators can only have "
"one Crew on a Group."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1383
msgid "Crew Card Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1386
msgid ""
"Each Group may have at most two Crew Cards, and only one Crew with the "
"same title (e.g., a Group can't have two Engineers).\n"
"\n"
"All Crew Cards that improve Weapon Class have no impact in terrain that "
"modifies Weapon Class (e.g., ships in a Group with an Admiral would still"
" fire as E-Class in Asteroids), unless otherwise noted.\n"
"\n"
"When playing with Crew Cards, the 4 Resource Cards for Heroic Ships "
"cannot make ships Heroic. Instead, they can be played at any time to draw"
" 2 Crew Cards and keep 1."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1392
msgid ""
"12.2.3 Crew Card Limitations: Each Group may have at most two Crew Cards,"
" and only one Crew with the same title (e.g., a Group can’t have two "
"Engineers). All Crew Cards that improve Weapon Class have no impact in "
"terrain that modifies Weapon Class (e.g., ships in a Group with an "
"Admiral would still fire as E-Class in Asteroids), unless otherwise "
"noted. When playing with Crew Cards, the 4 Resource Cards for Heroic "
"Ships cannot make ships Heroic. Instead, they can be played at any time "
"to draw 2 Crew Cards and keep 1. 12.2.4 Crew Cards in Combat: After a "
"battle, each Crew Card in a Group that had at least one ship destroyed "
"must roll for survival and is eliminated on a roll of 9-10. Add +3 to the"
" roll if the Crew Card’s Group was eliminated and +3 if no friendly ships"
" remain in the battle hex after the battle (harder to pick up escape "
"pods). Crew Cards that become casualties are placed in the appropriate "
"discard pile. If a Crew Card survives even though its Group has been "
"destroyed, it is immediately assigned to another Group in its hex, if "
"possible. If not possible, during the next Economic Phase it must be "
"assigned as if it had been drawn. This does not prevent the player from "
"drawing a new Crew Card."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1398
msgid "Crew Cards in Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1401
msgid ""
"After a battle, each Crew Card in a Group that had at least one ship "
"destroyed must roll for survival and is eliminated on a roll of 9-10. Add"
" +3 to the roll if the Crew Card's Group was eliminated and +3 if no "
"friendly ships remain in the battle hex after the battle (harder to pick "
"up escape pods). Crew Cards that become casualties are placed in the "
"appropriate discard pile.\n"
"\n"
"If a Crew Card survives even though its Group has been destroyed, it is "
"immediately assigned to another Group in its hex, if possible. If not "
"possible, during the next Economic Phase it must be assigned as if it had"
" been drawn. This does not prevent the player from drawing a new Crew "
"Card."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1411
msgid ""
"Merchant Ship Pipelines represent groups of slow-moving space vessels as "
"well as navigational beacons and portions of space that have been charted"
" and cleared for space travel."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1416
msgid "MS Pipeline Characteristics"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1419
msgid ""
"Merchant Ship (MS) Pipelines always represent a single trade network – "
"never place a numeral marker underneath them. MS Pipelines move one hex "
"per turn, and do not receive any benefit from an increase in Movement "
"technology. They may be purchased and placed at a Shipyard in the usual "
"fashion. MS Pipelines are non-combat ships and do not incur maintenance "
"costs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1424
msgid "MS Pipelines Chains"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1427
msgid ""
"MS Pipelines may be organized in a \"chain\", a trade network connecting "
"planets and other regions of space. Two or more MS Pipelines adjacent to "
"one another form a chain (or pipeline). The benefits of a chain are "
"indicated below."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1435
msgid ""
"Any unit, including another MS Pipeline, that starts its movement on a "
"chain of friendly MS Pipeline counters and spends its entire Movement "
"Phase on the same chain may move an additional hex, as long as that hex "
"is also part of the chain. If used to aid a ship's movement, none of the "
"MS Pipeline counters that form this chain may move or have moved during "
"the turn.\n"
"\n"
"To make it easier to keep track of which MS Pipeline counters have not "
"moved, the MS Pipeline counters have an \"Active\" side. If a MS Pipeline"
" has moved, flip it to the \"Moved\" side until the start of the next "
"turn.\n"
"\n"
"MS Pipelines that survive entrance into a Black Hole hex may, in future "
"turns, use their navigational aids to allow friendly ships traveling "
"along a chain to enter the Black Hole hex without rolling for destruction"
" (in other words, a chain may extend into a Black Hole hex).\n"
"\n"
"MS Pipelines also allow friendly ships which are traveling along a chain "
"to ignore Nebulae and Asteroids for purposes of movement."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1446
msgid "Trade Networks"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1449
msgid ""
"Any friendly Colony (even a new one) that is connected to the Homeworld "
"by a friendly MS Pipeline chain produces one extra CP in the Economic "
"Phase (the Homeworld does not produce an extra CP, but each Colony "
"connected to its network does). There must be an MS Pipeline counter in "
"each planet hex, including the Homeworld, and in each hex in between.\n"
"\n"
"An unlimited number of Colonies may be connected to the Homeworld in this"
" way, each contributing an extra CP through the network. MS Pipelines may"
" contribute to this chain even if they moved this turn. Each Colony gives"
" this benefit only one time per Economic Phase, no matter how many times "
"it is connected."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1461
msgid ""
"14.0 Defense Satellite Networks 14.1 DSN CHARACTERISTICS Similar to Bases"
" (8.1), a Defense Satellite Network (DSN) may be built at any friendly "
"planet with an income-producing Colony (not new or blockaded Colonies). "
"DSNs cannot move and do not incur maintenance costs. DSNs are not built "
"by Shipyards; however, they cannot be built until a player has researched"
" Ship Size 2 technology. 14.2 DSN RESTRICTIONS Each Colony is limited to "
"one DSN and one Base/Starbase (38.5). If a Colony builds a DSN during an "
"Economic Phase, it may not build a Base (or upgrade a Base to a Starbase)"
" during the same Economic Phase. 14.3 DSN COMBAT DSNs (B4-1-x2) "
"participate in combat like other Groups, but may not retreat and cannot "
"be boarded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1467
msgid "DSN Characteristics"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1470
msgid ""
"Similar to Bases (8.1), a Defense Satellite Network (DSN) may be built at"
" any friendly planet with an income-producing Colony (not new or "
"blockaded Colonies). DSNs cannot move and do not incur maintenance costs."
"\n"
"\n"
"DSNs are not built by Shipyards; however, they cannot be built until a "
"player has researched Ship Size 2 technology."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1477
msgid "DSN Restrictions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1480
msgid ""
"Each Colony is limited to one DSN and one Base/Starbase (38.5). If a "
"Colony builds a DSN during an Economic Phase, it may not build a Base (or"
" upgrade a Base to a Starbase) during the same Economic Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1485
msgid "DSN Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1488
msgid ""
"DSNs (B4-1-x2) participate in combat like other Groups, but may not "
"retreat and cannot be boarded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1493
msgid "Carriers, Fighters, & Point Defense"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1496
msgid ""
"Fighter technology allows you to build Carriers (CV) and Fighter "
"Squadrons. Point Defense technology applies only to Scouts, and only "
"affects their attacks against Fighters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1501
msgid "Carriers (CV)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1512
msgid ""
"A Carrier may hold a maximum of 3 Fighter Squadrons. Carriers may "
"participate in combat but cannot be targeted until all friendly Fighters "
"(not just those on that particular Carrier) present in the battle are "
"destroyed (even if the Carrier is screened). Carriers lose this immunity "
"if their owner screens any Fighters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1517
msgid "Carrier Retreats"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1520
msgid ""
"Carriers that retreat may not \"orphan\" Fighters in combat. A Carrier "
"may retreat with less than its full complement of Fighter Squadrons, but "
"only if there are specific ships (15.2.3) or a friendly Colony remaining "
"in the System to absorb the Fighters left behind."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1525
msgid "Fighters (F)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1536
msgid ""
"Fighters are purchased in squadrons, and numeral markers are used "
"underneath Fighter Squadron counters to indicate the number of squadrons "
"represented by that counter. Note: Fighter Squadron counters are not "
"physically stacked on a Carrier, they just need to be in the same hex.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A hex could have one Carrier Group with a 2 under the counter "
"and one Fighter Group with a 6 under the counter to represent two fully "
"loaded Carriers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1543
msgid "Fighter Movement"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1546
msgid ""
"Fighters are small spaceships that have no interstellar movement "
"capability of their own. Fighter Squadrons therefore may not move from "
"hex to hex on their own, although they may be carried."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1551
msgid "Carrying Fighters"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1554
msgid ""
"Only Carriers (15.1), Battle Carriers (38.6), Titans (22.0), or Unique "
"Ships with Mini-Fighter Bays (p.45) may carry Fighter Squadrons. Thus, a "
"squadron must remain at the Shipyard where it is placed during the "
"Economic Phase, or transfer to one of the above-noted ships in the same "
"hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1559
msgid "Transfer"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1562
msgid ""
"One or more Fighter Squadrons may transfer from a colonized planet to an "
"appropriate ship type (or vice versa) which is in the same hex. Fighters "
"may also transfer between ships in the same hex. Transfer may happen any "
"time during a ship's move or during combat at no extra cost to the ship, "
"but movement is simultaneous. A Fighter Squadron cannot be moved further "
"in one turn than the speed of the fastest ship involved.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A player may not use Move 4 to move a CV and 3 Fighters two "
"hexes to an empty CV and then have the second CV move 2 hexes with the 3 "
"Fighters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1569
msgid "Fighters & Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1572
msgid ""
"A Fighter Squadron is counted as a single combat-capable ship for the "
"purpose of determining screening. Fighters may not fire on the turn their"
" carrying ship declares it is retreating. Fighters that declare they are "
"retreating remain in the battle until the ship that is carrying them "
"retreats (15.1.2). They still protect the carrying ship as normal from "
"enemy fire until it retreats, or until the Fighters are destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1577
msgid "Fighters and Colonies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1580
msgid ""
"There is no limit to the number of Fighter Squadrons that may be on a "
"planet with a Colony. Fighters based on a Colony must participate in any "
"battle that occurs in its hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1585
msgid "Fighter Technology & Upgrades"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1588
msgid ""
"Fighter technology improves a Fighter's Attack and Defense Strength (as "
"indicated on the Ship Chart). In addition to upgrading the technology "
"they carry (9.11.3) Fighters may also upgrade their basic attack and "
"defense by upgrading the Fighter Technology level, this is done similarly"
" and at the same time and at no extra cost as all other technologies.\n"
"\n"
"All Fighters that are Fighter 2 or 3 get +1 Defense against Point Defense"
" (15.3)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1595
msgid "Point Defense Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1598
msgid ""
"Point Defense is a technology that is equipped by Scouts and used against"
" Fighters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1603
msgid "Scouts"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1606
msgid ""
"Point Defense technology improves a Scout's ability to contend with "
"Fighters. A Scout with Point Defense technology has an A-Class rating and"
" a higher Attack Strength (depending on the Point Defense level), but "
"only when firing at Fighter Squadrons; even then, all other capabilities "
"remain the same. In combat, a Scout with Point Defense technology firing "
"at a target other than a Fighter Squadron does so with its normal E-Class"
" rating.\n"
"\n"
"Exception: In Asteroids and Nebulae, Point Defense equipped ships have an"
" E-Class rating like all other ships and Fighters."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1613
msgid "Scouts and Attack/Defense Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1616
msgid ""
"Point Defense technology can be used with Attack and Defense technology "
"when Scouts combat Fighters – up to the limit of their Hull Size, which "
"is 1 in both cases.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Scout (E-Class, Attack Strength 3) with Point Defense "
"technology level 1 (A6 vs. Fighters) plus Attack technology level 1 (+1 "
"to Attack Strength) would fire on Fighters with an A7 and fire on non-"
"Fighters with an E4."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1631
msgid "Raiders (R)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1634
msgid ""
"Cloaking technology allows the purchase of Raiders. Raiders have the "
"additional ability to cloak. When a Raider's Cloaking technology is "
"superior to the enemy's Scanner technology (16.2), or the enemy has no "
"Scanners, then the Raider is considered cloaked."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1639
msgid "Movement Advantage"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1642
msgid ""
"A cloaked Raider may move into a hex occupied by an enemy unit and "
"continue moving. It need not stop. It may also occupy a hex and not "
"trigger combat. If a cloaked Raider is in the same hex as an enemy ship, "
"the Colony is not considered blockaded (7.1.2). The cloaked Raider would "
"have to defeat any enemy ships to blockade a Colony."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1647
msgid "Retreat Advantage"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1650
msgid ""
"At the start of a battle, cloaked Raiders (both Attacking and Defending) "
"have the option to retreat after the fleets are revealed and before shots"
" are fired or Mines detonate (17.1.5). In this case, if no other ships "
"remained in combat, information about an opponent's technology would not "
"be revealed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1655
msgid "Firing Advantage"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1658
msgid ""
"In combat, cloaked Raiders (both Attacking and Defending) have an A-Class"
" rating and – during the first firing round only – have their Attack "
"Strength increased by +1. Uncloaked Raiders have a D-Class rating."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1663
msgid "Cloaking Technology Levels"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1666
msgid ""
"A player can increase his Cloaking technology up to level 2. Level 1 "
"Scanners do not negate level 2 Cloaking technology."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1671
msgid "Cloaking in Nebulae"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1674
msgid ""
"Cloaking devices do not work in Nebulae. All Raider ships are treated as "
"normal ships when in a Nebula."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1682
msgid ""
"To counteract Cloaking technology, a player may research Scanners. This "
"technology gives Destroyers (and Advanced Bases) the ability to scan for "
"Raiders. When a Destroyer with scanners is present, treat all enemy "
"Raiders (of equal or lower Cloaking level) as uncloaked. If all scanner "
"equipped Destroyers are eliminated, the enemy ships regain the benefits "
"of being cloaked at the start of the next firing round. To avoid this, a "
"player may combat screen a Destroyer as long as they outnumber their "
"opponent. A screened Destroyer may not participate in combat, but still "
"provides its fleet with scanning benefits.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A player moves their Raiders into a hex with an enemy fleet and "
"either wants to skip combat or keep moving and so announces that they are"
" Raiders. The other player desires combat and so announces that they have"
" Scanners present. The Raider player then announces that their Raiders "
"are at Cloaking 2. The enemy player might then announce that they have "
"Scanner 2."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1700
msgid ""
"Mine technology must be researched before Mines may be purchased and "
"placed on the game board. A Mines counter operates like any other Group; "
"a numeral marker must be placed under it to indicate the number of Mines "
"represented by the counter. Mines cost no maintenance."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1705
msgid "Mine Movement"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1708
msgid ""
"The Mine counter may move on its own, but it is limited to a movement of "
"one hex regardless of technology level."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1716
msgid ""
"Mines may not explore or enter an enemy occupied hex (including one with "
"an enemy Colony) – even when accompanied by other friendly units. If "
"enemy ships enter a hex containing Mines, the Mines are automatically "
"considered deployed and active."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1721
msgid "Mines and Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1724
msgid ""
"After technology is revealed (9.10), all Minesweepers (17.2) remove as "
"many Mines as they are capable of sweeping. Unswept Mines immediately "
"detonate (the Mine counters are removed from play), destroying one ship "
"each (regardless of the type of the ship). Mines may target Fighter "
"Groups; one Mine will kill one Fighter. The choice of which ship is "
"destroyed is determined by the player who controls the Mines (yes, I'm "
"picking the DN!). If a ship carrying Fighters is destroyed by a Mine, the"
" Fighters present will be destroyed only if there is not enough room to "
"carry them on other ships. After Mine sweeping and detonation, combat "
"continues as normal. Mine sweeping and Mine detonation only happen at the"
" start of a battle."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1729
msgid "Must Detonate"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1732
msgid ""
"If enemy ships are present, Mines must detonate – they may not choose to "
"ignore a ship. It is therefore a legitimate strategy to attempt to clear "
"Mines by attacking with only Scouts. If there are more Mines than "
"attacking ships, excess Mines remain in the hex. Except when dealing with"
" cloaked ships, under no circumstances will both Mines and enemy ships "
"remain in a hex after the sweeping and detonating of Mines."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1737
msgid "Mines and Raiders"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1740
msgid ""
"Mines only work on Cloaked Raiders if there is a Destroyer with "
"appropriate Scanner technology present. This is the only exception to "
"Mines being in the same hex as enemy ships after detonation. If a "
"Destroyer with Scanner technology enters the hex, the Mines will activate"
" during combat. During combat (not movement), a cloaked ship can decide "
"to sacrifice itself and uncloak to allow a Mine to detonate on it, but if"
" other ships are present, the owner of the Mine is still free to choose "
"the Mine's target."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1745
msgid "Minesweepers (SW)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1748
msgid ""
"Minesweeper technology allows the purchase and placement of Minesweeper "
"units. Unlike Mines, Minesweepers move using the player's Movement "
"technology (they are not limited to a movement rate of one hex). "
"Minesweepers with Minesweeper technology level 1 remove one Mine each "
"before they detonate. Minesweeper 2 allows each Minesweeper to remove two"
" Mines before detonation. Minesweeper 3 allows each to remove three Mines"
" before detonation. Note that Minesweepers may be chosen as the target of"
" a detonating Mine, but they do not have to be."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1761
msgid "Placement"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1764
msgid ""
"Deep Space is inhabited by Non-Player Aliens (NPAs). When a System marker"
" in Deep Space is revealed to be a Barren Planet, random NPA ship markers"
" are drawn and placed on the planet according to the Deep Space Planet "
"Attribute (26.0). If not playing with that rule, draw 4. They attack any "
"ship that enters their hex, including their exploring ship. Combat is "
"resolved normally. If this planet was discovered by a Cruiser, Flagship, "
"or Replicator Exp ship using Exploration 1 (9.8), the aliens are placed "
"face down, unlooked at, and may not be examined."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1769
msgid "Alien Behavior"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1772
msgid ""
"Aliens normally don't leave their hex and never retreat.\n"
"\n"
"- Aliens have a Tactics level of 1.\n"
"- All NPA ships are equipped with Security Forces 1 (20.0).\n"
"- All NPA ships with a hull size of 1 have PD2 (15.3).\n"
"- All NPA ships with a hull size of 2 have Scanner 1. However, they will "
"only use this ability when attacked. They will not stop cloaked fleets "
"that do not attack.\n"
"- Once an NPA planet hex is entered by an enemy ship, all NPA ships are "
"revealed and remain that way until the end of the game (unless captured, "
"21.12).\n"
"\n"
"The first non-team player to the left of the active player makes "
"decisions on the alien targets. In solitaire or coop games, players "
"should make decisions on behalf of the NPA that will work towards the "
"aliens' victory over the player."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1785
msgid "Conquering Alien Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1788
msgid ""
"Aliens do not normally get additional ships and are considered subdued "
"the moment they lose their last ship in combat. The (former) alien planet"
" can then be colonized normally by a player with Terraforming technology "
"(9.7).\n"
"===\n"
"\n"
"La suite (section 19.0) commence en page 19 mais je me suis arrêté à la "
"section 18.3 car les pages 11-19 s'arrêtent là pour les sections "
"complètes demandées (8.0-18.0). La section 19.0 (Boarding & Capturing "
"Ships) déborde sur la page 19 mais fait partie d'une section distincte "
"au-delà de 18.0.\n"
"\n"
"Cependant, puisque la page 19 contient aussi les sections 19.x, voici la "
"suite visible sur la page 19 :"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1806
msgid "Properties of Boarding Ships (BD)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1809
msgid ""
"Boarding Technology allows the purchase of Boarding Ships. Boarding Ships"
" have the following properties:\n"
"\n"
"- May make Boarding Attacks (see below).\n"
"- If combat occurs in Asteroids or a Nebula, Boarding Ships still fire as"
" F-Class, not E-Class (5.8).\n"
"- Like other ships, Boarding Ships always hit on a 1.\n"
"- Boarding Ships may not mount Attack technology."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1819
msgid "Boarding Attacks"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1830
msgid ""
"A Boarding Ship's attack is handled differently than a regular ship's "
"attack. The Hull Size of the ship being attacked is subtracted from the "
"Attack Strength of the Boarding Ship. All other modifiers and "
"technologies are ignored (do not use Attack Tech, Defense Tech, Fleet "
"Size Bonus, etc.) except for Experience modifiers (37.0) and Security "
"Forces (20.0). If that \"To Hit\" number or less is rolled, the attacked "
"ship has been captured by the boarding parties (multiple hits are not "
"required to take over a ship – regardless of Hull Size, one successful "
"boarding attack will take over an enemy ship).\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Veteran Boarding Ship (F5) is attacking a Legendary Cruiser. "
"The attack would succeed only on a roll of 1; that is 5 minus a Hull Size"
" of 3 (one larger for a Legendary Cruiser) minus an Experience modifier "
"of 1 (the target ship is 2 levels of Experience higher).\n"
"\n"
"Boarding Ships may attack each round regardless of the success or failure"
" of previous attempts. Boarding Ships may acquire Experience when they "
"successfully capture a ship."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1839 app/data/master_rulebook.py:3093
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:4325
msgid "Restrictions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1842
msgid ""
"The following restrictions apply to Boarding Attacks:\n"
"\n"
"- Carriers (15.1) and Battle Carriers (38.6) are protected from being "
"targeted by their Fighters as for normal attacks.\n"
"- Ships that are screened (5.7) from combat cannot be attacked and "
"therefore cannot be captured.\n"
"- Bases, Starbases, Defense Satellite Networks, Shipyards, Colonies, "
"Titans, Fighters, Doomsday Machines, Space Amoebas, Replicator ships "
"(40.0), and Transport Ships that are carrying any cargo may not be "
"captured and are instead engaged with a normal F1 attack if a Boarding "
"Ship fires on them. When using their F1 attack, Boarding Ships may get "
"the benefit of the Fleet Size Bonus but never benefit from Attack "
"technology.\n"
"\n"
"PLAY NOTE: Boarding Ships may be boarded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1856
msgid ""
"A ship captured by a boarding party immediately becomes controlled by the"
" capturing player. A captured ship has the following properties:\n"
"\n"
"- May not attack or retreat in the first full round immediately following"
" capture (the boarding parties are in the process of gaining complete "
"control of the ship).\n"
"- Does not count for Combat Screening (5.7) or Fleet Size bonus (5.1.3) "
"on the round after they are captured.\n"
"- May be fired upon, screened, and may be recaptured.\n"
"- May attack and retreat normally after the first round, post-capture. If"
" playing with Ship Experience (37.0), newly captured ships from other "
"players are Green (regardless of Military Academy level) but gain "
"Experience normally.\n"
"- If playing with Ship Experience, captured NPA ships (18.0) are always "
"Green and can never increase in Experience.\n"
"- Alternate Empire ships self-destruct when captured, but yield a "
"technology benefit. See 24.1 for details."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1868
msgid "Tracking Captured Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1871
msgid ""
"Until the end of the battle, a captured ship may be represented by "
"whatever spare counter is available. If either player has a free counter "
"of that unit type, it can be used. Barring that, a spare alien or other "
"counter may be used.\n"
"\n"
"At the conclusion of the battle, any surviving captured ships must be "
"switched over and represented by the player's own counters. A player "
"capturing a ship may have to scuttle other ships or combine other "
"counters to free up a Group counter to represent the captured ship "
"(7.3.2). If they are unwilling, they must scuttle the captured ship. If "
"it has the same technology as one of your Groups, the Group counters can "
"be combined.\n"
"\n"
"The new Group of captured ship(s) must have the appropriate technology "
"marked on the Ship Technology Sheet like any other Group. The former "
"owner of the ship must inform the player of the current technology levels"
" on the sheet.\n"
"\n"
"Until upgraded or scuttled, a player must always identify a formerly "
"captured ship in battle. The original owner would recognize their former "
"ship, and this makes it easier for them to try to destroy it, preventing "
"its technology from falling into enemy hands.."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1882
msgid "Captured Ships & Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1885
msgid ""
"Captured ships may use all the technologies that they possess. However, "
"they may not give the technology to other ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1890
msgid "Scrapping Technology"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1893
msgid ""
"If a captured ship is at a friendly Shipyard during an Economic Phase, it"
" may be scrapped for its technology. The scrapping player will gain one "
"level of technology in each area where the captured ship has better "
"technology, then the scrapped ship is removed. The player may "
"successively scrap multiple ships in the same Economic Phase to gain more"
" technology. The order in which they scrap ships is up to them. The "
"player may also purchase a level of a particular technology in the same "
"Economic Phase, either before or after scrapping a ship.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A player with Movement 1, Attack 2, Defense 1, and Tactics 1 "
"captures a ship that has Movement 3, Attack 2, Defense 2, and Tactics 0. "
"Upon scrapping the ship, the player gains Movement 2 and Defense 2 "
"technology. If the player had another ship just like this one and "
"scrapped it also, they would immediately gain Move 3 technology. The "
"player could then choose to use CP to purchase Move 4 technology.\n"
"\n"
"The following restrictions apply to Scrapping technology:\n"
"\n"
"- Scrapping a Carrier can only yield up to Fighter technology level 1, "
"regardless of the level of Fighter technology the other player possessed."
"\n"
"- Ground Combat technology cannot be gained by scrapping a Transport "
"(21.1).\n"
"- Security Forces (20.0) and Military Academies (37.2) – both of which "
"are not shown on the Ship Technology Sheet – cannot be gained by "
"capturing a ship.\n"
"- Any technology gained is limited to what is present on the ship being "
"scrapped.\n"
"- In a game with more than two players and no teams, players cannot gain "
"technology by scrapping captured ships. This is to prevent gamey tactics "
"and/or collusion between players to advance their technology levels.\n"
"\n"
"PLAY NOTE: Ship Size technology can be gained by this method."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1907
msgid "PLAY NOTE: Boarding Ships may be boarded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1913
msgid "Captured Non-Player Alien Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1916
msgid ""
"NPAs (18.0) may be captured. These incur maintenance costs and may be "
"used like any of a player's ships. However, a player may never put any of"
" their technology on an NPA ship. They have the standard NPA technology "
"(18.2) in addition to Movement 3 technology. They may be scuttled (7.3.2)"
" but may not be scrapped to gain technology (19.5.1). If stacked with "
"friendly ships, it should be obvious which Empire owns them. If moved on "
"their own, they can be marked using one of the player's Empire markers "
"which have been provided for this purpose."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1924
msgid ""
"This technology is only used in conjunction with Boarding Ships. If a "
"player researches Security Forces 1, all of their ships immediately and "
"automatically get a +1 to their Hull Size when being attacked by a "
"Boarding Ship (a ship does not need to be upgraded to get this benefit, "
"9.11.3). Security Forces 2 doubles this benefit (+2 total). This "
"represents a player developing a coherent plan for dealing with Boarding "
"Ships and communicating it to their fleet.\n"
"\n"
"All NPA ships (18.0) are equipped with Security Forces 1."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1939
msgid "Transports"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1950
msgid ""
"At the start of game, all players have Ground Combat 1, allowing them to "
"build Transports and Infantry. Transports are used to carry Ground Units "
"and Fighters (15.2). They may also be used to transport Dilithium "
"Crystals (see the Deep Space Planet Attributes) and Logistic Points "
"(36.5) if using those rules.\n"
"\n"
"Transports do not need to stop to pick up or drop off Ground Units or "
"Fighters; they can pick them up while passing a planet in a similar way "
"to a CV picking up Fighters (15.2.3). Fighters that were carried on "
"Transports may not participate in combat that same player turn, even if "
"transferred to another ship or Colony.\n"
"\n"
"Transports have the following properties:\n"
"\n"
"- May not explore.\n"
"- Each may carry any combination of up to 6 Ground Units and/or Fighters "
"or 30 Logistic Points (36.5.6).\n"
"- A loaded Transport may not be boarded (19.2).\n"
"- If a Transport is destroyed, its owner destroys any Ground Units, "
"Dilithium Crystals or Logistic Points now in excess of Transport "
"Capacity.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A player has 2 Transports, 5 Space Marines and 3 Infantry "
"involved in a battle. One of the Transports is destroyed. The player must"
" remove 2 Ground Units because only 6 may fit on the remaining Transport."
" They choose to eliminate 2 of the Infantry.\n"
"\n"
"- Transports participate in space combat normally. They may fire, may be "
"screened, etc.\n"
"- Transports cannot land units on a planet that is protected by Mines. "
"(For Example: The Missed Rendezvous Resource Card combined with the Anti-"
"Sensor Hulls Unique Ship Ability can lead to this quirky situation.)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1966
msgid "PLAY NOTE: Ship Size technology can be gained by this method."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1972
msgid "Upgrading Transports (Drop Ships)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1975
msgid ""
"When a player researches Ground Combat 3, their Transports may be "
"upgraded so that their Defense Strength increases from 1 to 2 (Armored "
"Transports). The Transports will also be equipped with \"Drop Ships,\" "
"which allow invading Ground Units to attack in the first round of ground "
"combat. In addition, the player may purchase Grav Armor."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1980
msgid "Ground Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1983
msgid ""
"Each Ground Unit represents a massive number of troops. Ground Units come"
" in 6 varieties: Infantry, Space Marines, Heavy Infantry, Militia, Grav "
"Armor, and Cyber Armor. Ground Units have the following properties:\n"
"\n"
"- Require no maintenance cost.\n"
"- May not be placed on an uncolonized planet.\n"
"- Provide a defensive benefit against bombardment (21.6) and may not be "
"hit by bombardment (21.7.4).\n"
"- Ground Units play no part in space combat. Whether on a Colony or on a "
"Transport, they never shoot at ships, and they may never be shot at by "
"ships.\n"
"- Are eliminated if not on a Colony or if in excess of Transport capacity."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1994
msgid "Purchasing Ground Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:1997
msgid ""
"A number of Ground Units equal to the CP number of a Colony may be "
"purchased at that un-blockaded Colony during an Economic Phase (no "
"Shipyard is needed for any).\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A Colony produced 3 CP that Economic Phase. Any mixture of three"
" Ground Units may be placed there after they are purchased."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2007
msgid ""
"Militia units are never purchased. They are temporarily awarded when a "
"Colony is invaded: 1 Militia per CP number on the Colony. This is in "
"addition to any Ground Units which are already on the planet. This "
"represents the police forces, etc., and the difficulty in conquering a "
"planet. Even if these Militia units are destroyed, if the planet is "
"subsequently invaded, it will again be awarded Militia units equal to the"
" CP on the Colony.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: A planet with a 3 CP marker on it will be temporarily awarded 3 "
"Militia units if attacked by Ground Units. A Homeworld could yield as "
"many as 30 Militia units!"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2014
msgid "Free Ground Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2017
msgid ""
"A player receives one free Ground Unit for every three, un-blockaded 5 CP"
" Colonies (not the Homeworld) that they have at the start of an Economic "
"Phase (rounded down). This is in addition to any units that are "
"purchased. Think of this as skimming off the population growth of the "
"more adventuresome colonists once the Colony is at full strength.\n"
"\n"
"The free units are Infantry if at Ground Combat 1 when the units are "
"placed or they can be Heavy Infantry or Space Marines at Ground Combat 2 "
"(21.10). Grav Armor and Cyber Armor (38.7) can never be received for "
"free; they must be purchased (21.11). The free units are placed at any "
"un-blockaded 5 CP Colony or Homeworld, one per Colony. This does not "
"count against the purchased unit limit."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2024
msgid "Planetary Defense"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2027
msgid ""
"Ground Units contribute to planetary defense. Think of them as being "
"armed with lots of surface-to-air missiles that keep the bombarding ships"
" at arm's length. If there are Ground Units besides Militia on the planet"
" when the Colony is being bombarded (21.7.4), the Colony is considered to"
" have a Defense Strength of 1 if there 1-3 Ground Units present. With 4 "
"or more Ground Units present it has a Defense Strength of 2. Militia "
"never contributes to bombardment defense."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2032
msgid "Landing Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2035
msgid ""
"If a player's units move into a Colony hex that contains enemy Ground "
"Units but no combat-capable ships, both sides are revealed immediately. "
"All unrevealed units moving into the Colony hex must be revealed; "
"however, an exception is made for RaiderXs (38.9) and the Ground Units "
"they may be carrying. Decoys are removed and the non-moving player must "
"eliminate non-combat ships if the moving player has combat ships present."
" The moving player may now decide whether they wish to continue moving or"
" stay in that hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2040
msgid "Reaction Movements in Response"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2043
msgid ""
"Since a Reaction Move (35.0) by the non-moving player can normally only "
"be made after the moving player has finished moving, the Reaction Move "
"would happen only after the non-moving player's non-combat ships had been"
" eliminated, and then only if the moving player decided to stay in that "
"hex."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2048
msgid "Determine Location of Ground Units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2051
msgid ""
"If a player is defending in a hex with Ground Units, Transports, and a "
"friendly Colony, that player must decide after the fleets have been "
"revealed, but before combat, whether their Ground Units are on the planet"
" or on the Transports (or a mixture of both)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2056
msgid "Landing"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2059
msgid ""
"After the SECOND ROUND of space combat and after each round thereafter, "
"players may decide to land Ground Units on a Colony in that hex. Any "
"Ground Units on the Transports are simply placed on the planet (Ground "
"Combat will be resolved when Space Combat is done). A Transport may land "
"Ground Units this way even if it had been screened. If the planet is "
"Barren, then Ground Units may only be landed if their Empire has "
"Terraforming 1.\n"
"\n"
"Regardless of whether Ground Units are landed, Transports remain in the "
"battle and the space combat continues as normal."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2066
msgid "Bombardment"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2069
msgid ""
"After space combat is over and before ground combat occurs, the attacker "
"may decide to bombard the Colony (5.10) before landing any Ground Units. "
"Bombardment cannot take place once the attacker has landed any units. The"
" player may roll attacks against the Colony one at a time, reducing it, "
"until they decide to land their Ground Units. Once they have landed their"
" units, they may not bombard the Colony anymore that turn, even if the "
"invasion goes poorly."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2074
msgid "Ground Combat Procedure"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2077
msgid ""
"Ground combat is resolved after all space combat in the hex is finished. "
"Like space combat, Ground Units fire at each other in order of Weapon "
"Class (D-Class before E-Class), take damage, and are eliminated when they"
" take damage equal to their \"Hull Size\" (not that Ground Units have "
"hulls, but for simplicity's sake they use the same metric)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2082
msgid "Unused Mechanics"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2085
msgid ""
"Ships, Fleet Size Bonus, Tactics, and Attack/Defense Tech have no effect "
"on ground combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2090
msgid "No Retreating"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2093
msgid ""
"Ground combat continues indefinitely until one side wins. There is no "
"Retreat from ground combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2098
msgid "Attacker Disadvantage"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2101
msgid ""
"Ties in Weapon Class always result in the defender firing first. Any "
"Ground Units dropped off by Transports without Drop Ships (available with"
" Ground Combat 3), may not fire in the first round of ground combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2106
msgid "Ground Combat Screening"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2109
msgid ""
"Combat Screening (5.7) can be used in ground combat. Units that cannot "
"fire do not count when determining which units can be screened. A spare "
"counter of the appropriate type of unit can be used to place in the "
"\"screened units\" portion of the Battle Board (37.4.2). In the case of "
"Transports being used as Air Support (see the Card Manifest), a Transport"
" can be screened provided a spare Transport counter is available. A "
"player is not limited by the single Air Support counter provided. In the "
"case of Militia or Heavy Infantry Militia (Defending Familiar Terrain, "
"see the Card Manifest), a player may screen some of the Militia while "
"leaving some of them in combat by using any spare counter to keep track "
"of how many are being screened in each combat round."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2114
msgid "Determine Victor"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2122
msgid "Defender Victory"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2125
msgid ""
"If the defender destroys the last attacking Ground Unit, the Colony has "
"been successfully defended and any remaining Militia units are removed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2130
msgid "Attacker Victory"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2133
msgid ""
"If the attacker destroys the last defending Ground Unit (including "
"Militia), the Colony has been successfully captured (21.13). To complete "
"the process, the attacker must remove one Ground Unit that is on the "
"planet (even if the attacker is recapturing a planet that was previously "
"their own.) The removal of this unit represents the permanent resources "
"needed to manage the captured Colony. The defeated Colony marker is left "
"in place and covered with one from the conquering player (21.13.3).\n"
"\n"
"Any Shipyards, Bases, Starbases, or Defense Satellite Networks (14.0) at "
"the Colony belonging to the defender are destroyed. This means it is "
"possible to drop Ground Units after the second round of space combat, "
"lose the space battle, yet still destroy the above-noted units. In such a"
" scenario, any of the defender's Fighters in excess of the carrying "
"capacity of their friendly CVs/BVs/Titans/Unique Ships are lost if their "
"Colony is captured. If an enemy fleet remains in orbit, they may not "
"bombard the Colony until their turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2140
msgid "Space Marines & Heavy Infantry"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2143
msgid ""
"Require Ground Combat 2. Space Marines and Heavy Infantry have different "
"Weapon Classes and Attack Strengths when they are attacking or defending."
" Marines attack at C6 and defend at D5. Heavy Infantry attack at D4 and "
"defend at C6."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2151
msgid ""
"Require Ground Combat 3. Grav Armor has a special ability beyond its "
"normal attack. At the start of each round of combat, for every Grav Armor"
" unit a player has over the amount that their opponent has, they can "
"provide support to one non-Grav Armor unit, including Militia (and "
"Transports if you have Air Support, see the Card Manifest). A supported "
"unit gains one to its Attack and Defense Strength. A unit can only be "
"supported by one Grav Armor unit per round. Units that cannot fire cannot"
" be supported and are not counted when determining how many units can be "
"supported.\n"
"\n"
"EXAMPLE: The defender has 3 Grav Armor, 1 Space Marine and 1 Militia on "
"the planet. The attacker has no Grav Armor, so the defender can support 3"
" units. As they only have 2 non-Grav Armor units the 3rd support bonus is"
" lost. The Space Marine will fire as a D6 unit with a Defense Strength of"
" 2 for this round. The Militia will fire as an E6 unit with a Defense "
"Strength of 1 for this round."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2158
msgid "Ground Combat Against Aliens"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2161
msgid ""
"Non-player Aliens (18.0) are a special case with several exceptions to "
"ground combat:\n"
"\n"
"- They may only be invaded if a player has Terraforming 1.\n"
"- They may not be invaded until their fleet is destroyed. This means that"
" Ground Units may not be landed after the second round of combat as is "
"usually allowed (21.7.3).\n"
"- After defeating the NPA fleet, the player may colonize it normally or "
"choose to invade.\n"
"- NPA Alien planets do not yield technology benefits other than the Alien"
" Technology cards (11.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2174
msgid ""
"The NPAs have 5 Militia units on the planet. If these are defeated, the "
"player places a 3 CP Colony of their color on the planet. If the NPAs are"
" not defeated in ground combat, the planet is considered subdued from "
"space and may be colonized normally; it may not be invaded later. A "
"player has only one shot to invade an NPA planet and that is immediately "
"after destroying its fleet. A player may NOT bombard the Colony to reduce"
" the number of Militia like they could with a human player (21.7.4)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2182
msgid ""
"When a player invades a Colony on an NPA planet that was started by "
"another player using their Amazing Diplomats ability (see the Card "
"Manifest), that Colony may be invaded after Round 2 as normal. If the "
"attacker wins the ground combat, any remaining NPA ships still defending "
"the planet that were not boarded/captured by the attacker during space "
"combat are destroyed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2187
msgid "Captured Colonies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2195
msgid "Procedure and Properties"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2198
msgid ""
"Captured Colonies \"go backward\" one step of growth upon capture. A 5 CP"
" Colony becomes a 3 CP Colony, a 3 CP Colony becomes a 1 CP Colony, and a"
" 1 CP Colony is flipped back to its Colony Ship side. In this last case "
"it does not actually become a ship, it just reverts to that step in the "
"growth process. (This is the only time a Colony is ever flipped back to "
"the Colony Ship side.) It will grow to 1 CP in the following Economic "
"Phase. In the rare case where a Colony with only a Colony Ship would be "
"captured, replace the Colony Ship with one of the capturing player's. The"
" captured Colony is then treated like any of the capturing player's "
"Colonies. It will provide income and grow, Shipyards may be built, "
"Militia will be produced when attacked, etc. Any Minerals (6.7) and Space"
" Wrecks (6.8) that are on the Colony when it is captured are destroyed "
"with no benefit."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2203
msgid "Captured Homeworlds"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2206
msgid ""
"A conquered Homeworld becomes a normal Colony (max 5 CP) for the "
"conqueror."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2211
msgid "Indicate Captured Status"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2214
msgid ""
"The Colony marker from the defeated player is left on the planet and "
"covered by the new owner because the captured status of the Colony "
"continues to impact the game. The original owner and their allies may not"
" attack their former Colony from space. If they want it back, they will "
"have to invade (the planet is filled with their own colonists!). If a "
"player is eliminated, do not remove any Colony markers that they have on "
"the board that have been captured by another player."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2219
msgid "Reveal Cards"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2222
msgid ""
"When a Colony is captured (not recaptured), the player who lost the "
"Colony must reveal to the capturing player all the Empire Advantages "
"(10.0) and Alien Tech cards (11.0) that they have at that moment."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2227
msgid "Capture in Enemy Home Systems"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2230
msgid ""
"When a Colony/Homeworld is captured (not recaptured) in an enemy player's"
" Home System, the capturing player may look at the enemy player's "
"Production Sheet and the capturing Empire immediately increases one level"
" in two technologies in which the other player is more advanced. This is "
"similar to capturing technology through scrapping captured ships except "
"that it happens immediately and not in the Economic Phase."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2235
msgid "Capture in Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2238
msgid ""
"If a Colony is captured (not recaptured) in Deep Space, it is handled the"
" same way as above, except that only one level of one technology may be "
"taken (capturing player's choice). If playing a scenario in which a "
"player's Home System markers are mixed with the Deep Space markers at "
"setup, then all Colonies besides the Homeworld count as Deep Space "
"planets for the purpose of this rule."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2243
msgid "Multiplayer Games"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2246
msgid ""
"In a multiplayer game that has no fixed teams you cannot gain technology "
"through capturing Colonies."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2251
msgid "Recaptured Colonies"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2254
msgid ""
"If a player recaptures a Colony that was previously their own, they do "
"not get any technology benefit/increase. Once a Colony is recaptured by "
"the original owner, all other Colony markers are removed."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2259
msgid "Capturing another Player's Captured Planet"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2262
msgid ""
"If a third player captures a planet, they gain technology from the "
"original owner, not the current owner. The technology that can be gained "
"is only that which was researched by the original player at the time it "
"was originally captured. In multiplayer games, a note should be made of "
"the player's technology when the planet is captured in case this happens."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2270
msgid ""
"Titans are massive ships – far larger than a DN.\n"
"\n"
"A player must have Ship Size 7 Tech (9.4) to build a Titan. Titans have "
"the following properties:\n"
"\n"
"- Each hit from a Titan does 2 damage to a single ship instead of 1. It "
"only gets 1 attack each round.\n"
"- May never be screened (5.7) due to their size.\n"
"- May never retreat (5.9) from combat.\n"
"- Are immune to Boarding Ships (19.2.2) due to their size.\n"
"- Unless the attacking ship is a Fighter, a roll of 1 is not an automatic"
" hit against a Titan. It is therefore possible for some ships to not be "
"able to score a hit on a Titan, depending on the technologies on the "
"ships.\n"
"- Fighters receive +1 to their Attack Strength against Titans. This is in"
" addition to any modifiers from Attack Technology (9.2) and Fleet Size "
"(5.1.3)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2284
msgid "Fleet Size Bonus"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2287
msgid ""
"Which side gets the Fleet Size Bonus (5.1.3) is calculated normally for "
"the battle. However, when firing at the Titan, ships other than Fighters "
"do not get to claim the bonus."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2292
msgid "Can Carry Fighters"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2295
msgid ""
"If the player with a Titan also has Fighter Tech, a Titan may carry 3 "
"Fighters in the same way as a Carrier (15.0). An existing Titan can be "
"upgraded to have this ability as soon as Fighter 1 is researched. "
"Although the Titan carries Fighters, it is not considered a Carrier. It "
"may be fired upon while friendly Fighters are still present in the "
"battle. In the unlikely event that a Titan is destroyed and there are "
"more Fighters left than can be carried on the remaining "
"CVs/BVs/Titans/Unique Ships/Advanced Flagships, the extra Fighters would "
"be eliminated at the conclusion of the battle."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2300
msgid "Planet Destroyers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2303
msgid ""
"A Titan may not attack a Colony like a normal ship would. When a Titan "
"fires at a Colony, the Colony and planet are both automatically "
"destroyed. Remove the planet from the game and replace it with one of the"
" Asteroid terrain tiles (5.8.1). This hex is now an Asteroid hex. A Titan"
" may fire at and destroy a planet that does not have a Colony on it."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2308
msgid "Titans & Mines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2311
msgid ""
"Because of their great size, Mines (17.0) do not kill a Titan, but do one"
" point of damage each. It would take 5 Mines to kill a Titan. If a battle"
" immediately follows Mine detonation, then the Titan would enter that "
"battle with damage. Fighters carried by the Titan are immune to any Mine "
"damage unless the Titan is destroyed, which would destroy them. All "
"damage is repaired at the end of a battle as normal."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2319
msgid ""
"Each player begins with one Flagship representing the crowning "
"achievement of an Empire (up to this point). A Flagship will always have "
"a 1 numeral marker underneath. Flagships have the following properties:\n"
"\n"
"- Pays no maintenance but counts as Hull Size 3 for upgrading technology "
"(9.11.3) and damage (5.6).\n"
"- May have their technology upgraded normally, may gain Experience "
"(37.0), and function as any other ship in all other respects.\n"
"- May be upgraded to carry Exploration 1 (9.8) and Fast 1 (9.9) once they"
" are researched.\n"
"- If destroyed, it can never be rebuilt. The destruction of a Flagship "
"does not hurt an Empire in any other way – the player simply loses the "
"use of it."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2329
msgid "Capture of Flagships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2332
msgid ""
"Flagships that are successfully boarded and captured (19.0) can be used "
"by the capturing player. In this case, the counter just continues to be "
"used by the capturing player. It operates like all other captured ships "
"except that it pays no maintenance. A separate note of its technology "
"will have to be kept on the Ship Technology Sheet."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2337
msgid "Names of Flagships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2340
msgid ""
"The Flagships are the only ships in the game that are named:\n"
"\n"
"- Enterprise (Blue) – Besides the obvious sci-fi and space shuttle "
"connection, the aircraft carrier USS Enterprise (CVN 65) was in her last "
"deployment at the time of the Close Encounters first printing.\n"
"- Victory – The name of Admiral Nelson's flagship at Trafalgar.\n"
"- Thunder Child – In H.G. Wells' book, War of the Worlds, this in an "
"ironclad ship that destroyed two Martian Tripods while covering the "
"escape of refugee ships.\n"
"- Argo – From Greek mythology – Jason and the Argonauts. It was also the "
"American name given to the Space Battleship Yamato in the Japanese movie "
"\"Star Blazers.\"\n"
"- Fearless – In \"honor\" of Honor Harrington's ship.\n"
"- Eagle – First LEM on the Moon and the name of the spacecraft in Space "
"1999."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2357
msgid ""
"24.0 Alternate Empires 24.1 INTRODUCTION & GENERAL RULES Alternate "
"Empires have ships with alternate costs and abilities than those found in"
" the base game. Up to two players can play Alternate Empires at once or "
"they can be played against original empires. The costs and capabilities "
"of their ships can be found on the Alternate Empire Production Sheet. "
"24.1.1 Different Units: Alternate Empires possess a new type of unit – "
"Missile Boats (24.4). They cannot research Fast 2 (9.9.2) and cannot "
"build Titans (except for the War Sun Empire Advantage, 10.0). 24.1.2 "
"Changes to Fighters: Alternate Empires have advanced Fighters that do not"
" require a ship to carry them when they move. As a result, these Empires "
"have no need to (and cannot) build CVs (15.1) or BVs (38.6). Alternate "
"Empire Fighters function the same as other combat-capable ships; When an "
"Alternate Empire gets the On Board Workshop Alien Technology Card (11.0),"
" it may be used on BBs and DNs. 24.1.3 Changes to Boarding: Alternate "
"Empires do not have Boarding Ships (19.0). If their ships are "
"successfully boarded, they are destroyed instead of being captured. How- "
"ever, every time a ship is successfully boarded, the boarding player may "
"steal one technology that was on the ship. If the Self Destruct Resource "
"Card is played it prevents this technology theft. A successful boarding "
"attack still counts as captured for the purpose of Ship Experience "
"(37.0). 24.2 Random Special Ability Selection For Battlecruisers, "
"Battleships, and Dreadnoughts a random special ability is drawn and made "
"available for that class to research at the times specified below. Each "
"ability can be researched for a cost of 10 CP. Note that the abilities "
"must be researched before they are available to use. When drawn, the "
"number of the ability should be written on the player’s Production Sheet."
" • Battle Cruisers: Draw a random special ability when Ship Size 4 is "
"researched. BCs do not automatically get Fast 1 (9.9). • Battleships: "
"Draw a random special ability when Advanced Construction 1 (38.0) is "
"researched. BBs do not automatically get Tractor Beams (p.45). • "
"Dreadnoughts: Draw a random special ability when Advanced Construction 1 "
"is researched. DNs do not automatically get Shield Projectors (p.45). • "
"Flagships: A Flagship may still be equipped with Exploration Technology "
"(9.8). However, instead of automatically getting Fast 1, it gets access "
"to the same special ability as the Battle Cruisers (see above) once it’s "
"been researched. When upgraded to an Advanced Flagship (38.11), it may "
"pick an ability off the Unique Ship Table like any other Advanced "
"Flagship."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:2363 app/data/master_rulebook.py:2769
#: app/data/master_rulebook.py:3914
msgid "Introduction & General Rules"
msgstr ""

