#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:153
msgid ""
"The play time for this game is in the 1 to 4-hour range for a solitaire "
"game, depending on the scenario. For cooperative games, the play time "
"will be at the higher end of that range.\n"
"• Start with just the basic rules. While they are fairly simple, the game"
" offers a lot of choices and decisions.\n"
"• Start with the 1-Player Small Doomsday Machine Scenario (2.7). This is "
"the least complex solitaire scenario.\n"
"• Be aggressive! This is a game that rewards aggressive play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:158
msgid ""
"Play Note: The Technology Head Start Scenario Card (see the Card "
"Manifest) is not available for solitaire or cooperative scenarios."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:163
msgid "Player Alliances in Coop Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:167
msgid ""
"All cooperative scenarios are played using the below rules for player "
"alliances.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.1 Allied Combat: Players may stack their units defensively and may "
"attack simultaneously, unless only some players act before the enemy, in "
"which case only those players move first.\n"
"\n"
"PLAY NOTE: In coop games versus two or more Alien Players, the APs may "
"also stack their units defensively and may attack simultaneously, if "
"able.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.2 Minerals: Players may tow Minerals to their ally's Colonies. The "
"Minerals will be used by that Colony's owner.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.3 MS Pipelines: Any human player may utilize another player's MS "
"Pipelines for the purposes of movement only.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.4 Allied Home Systems: Players may explore another player's Home "
"System just like they would any other unexplored hexes, but players may "
"not colonize another player's planets.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.5 Allied Colonies: Players may not capture Colonies from allies with "
"Ground Units (MRB 21.0) or use Boarding Ships (MRB 19.0) on allies. "
"Players may never bombard Colonies that your allies originally colonized."
"\n"
"\n"
"1.3.6 No Loans: Players may never give CP to each other.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.7 No Sharing Shipyards: Players may only upgrade their ships at their"
" own Shipyards."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:187
msgid "Expanded Sequence of Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:191
msgid ""
"This is NOT meant to be used in normal game play. This is meant to "
"resolve any disputes or confusion integrating all rules from the base "
"game and all three expansions.\n"
"\n"
"1. Determine Player Order (first turn of the game only)\n"
"\n"
"2. Turn One:\n"
"Player 1:\n"
"  a. Movement.\n"
"  b. Combat.\n"
"  c. Exploration. Note that if Exploration results in hostile forces in "
"the same hex return to Step b immediately and resolve the combat now.\n"
"Player(s) 2-8: Same as Player 1.\n"
"After all players have had a turn any Doomsday Machines on the map move.\n"
"\n"
"3. Turn Two: Same as turn one.\n"
"4. Turn Three: Same as turn one.\n"
"\n"
"5. Economic Phase -- All players conduct this phase simultaneously, not "
"in player order. Exception: Resource Cards played in Reverse Player "
"Order.\n"
"\n"
"MOVEMENT\n"
"Units may move from one hex to another at up to maximum speed. Movement "
"may be increased by MS Pipelines or Black Hole Slingshots, but not both. "
"Ships use Exploration markers before moving. One or more Resource Cards "
"may be played after Exploration tech is used but before any ship "
"movement.\n"
"\n"
"Raiders vs. Scanners: When the attacker moves into a hex with enemy units"
" and has Raiders:\n"
"• Attacker states they have Raiders and want to continue moving.\n"
"• Defender states Scanner 1 (attacker stops) or no Scanner 1 (attacker "
"continues).\n"
"• If Scanner 1, attacker may declare Cloaking 2.\n"
"• Defender states Scanner 2 (stop) or no Scanner 2 (continue).\n"
"The defender may choose not to announce their Scanner level.\n"
"\n"
"Black Hole Survival Checks happen before Reaction Movement and before "
"non-combat ships are destroyed.\n"
"\n"
"NON-COMBAT SHIPS SPECIAL MOVEMENT RULES\n"
"Units without Attack Strength may not enter hexes with enemy units, enemy"
" Colonies, or face-down System markers unless a friendly combat-capable "
"ship also enters. Destroyed if caught alone by combat-capable enemies.\n"
"\n"
"COMBAT\n"
"C1: Combat-capable units from two sides in same hex after movement.\n"
"C2: Defender may React.\n"
"C3: Attacker declares Cloaking; Defender declares Scanners.\n"
"C4: Defender declares Cloaking; Attacker declares Scanners.\n"
"C5: Play pre-reveal Resource Cards.\n"
"C6: Reveal ship types and numbers.\n"
"C7: Raiders with un-nullified cloak may retreat.\n"
"C8: Reveal tech, Empire Advantages, Alien Tech Cards, Experience levels.\n"
"C9: Attacker declares if cloaked Raiders join, Anti-Sensor Hull, Shield "
"Projectors.\n"
"C10: Defender declares if cloaked Raiders join, Shield Projectors.\n"
"C11: Play post-reveal Cards.\n"
"C12: Sweep Mines.\n"
"C13: Mines detonate.\n"
"C14: Screening determined.\n"
"C15: Tractor Beam targets declared.\n"
"C16: Round 1 of combat. A-Class defenders with Tactics 3 fire first. "
"Cloaked Raiders get +1 Attack.\n"
"C17: Horsemen of the Plains may retreat.\n"
"C18: Celestial Knights may charge.\n"
"C19: Re-determine screening and Tractor Beams.\n"
"Round 2+: Units may fire, not fire, or retreat.\n"
"C20: Attacker may drop Ground Units onto enemy Colony (if no Mines). "
"Defender may drop onto friendly Colony.\n"
"C21-C22: Horsemen/Celestial Knights.\n"
"C23: Continue until one side has no space combat-capable units.\n"
"C24: Play Planetary Bombardment Cards.\n"
"C25: Conduct Planetary Bombardment (if no Mines).\n"
"C26: Play Ground Combat Cards.\n"
"C27: Conduct Ground Combat (if no Mines).\n"
"C28: If Colony captured, reduce CP by one step. Remove one Ground Unit "
"for garrison. Capturing player may steal technologies.\n"
"\n"
"EXPLORATION\n"
"Units sharing space with a face-down System marker must explore it. Flip "
"and reveal. Apply effects immediately.\n"
"\n"
"ECONOMIC PHASE\n"
"E1: Replicator Colony Depletion (if applicable).\n"
"E2: Scrap Facilities.\n"
"E3: Draw Crew Cards (even-numbered phases).\n"
"E4: Draw Resource Card.\n"
"E5: Play Resource Cards (reverse player order).\n"
"E6: Discard/activate Cancel Cards.\n"
"E7: Collect CP/RP/LP/TP and free Ground Units.\n"
"E8: Determine Supply status.\n"
"E9: Record penalty CPs.\n"
"E10: Space Amoebas spread (may cause combat).\n"
"E11: Spend income.\n"
"E12: Place new units.\n"
"E13: Assign/discard Crew Cards.\n"
"E14: Adjust Colony counters for growth.\n"
"E15: Announce turn order bids.\n"
"E16: Discard Resource Cards for CP value.\n"
"E17: Discard Resource Cards over hand limit of 6."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:277
msgid "Comprehensive Example of Combat"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rules.py:281
msgid ""
"Yellow fleet: Colony Ship (non-combat x1), CV-1 (x2 with Fighters), CA-4 "
"(x2), BB-1 (x3), R-4 (x2)\n"
"Green fleet: SC-1 (x1), CA-4 (x2), Base-2 (x1), F-4 (x2), BC-1 (x2), SY-1"
" (x1), Colony, Mine (x1)\n"
"\n"
"Yellow (15 combat-capable + 1 non-combat) enters Green's hex.\n"
"\n"
"Detonate Mines: Yellow has no Minesweepers. Green targets a CV. The CV is"
" destroyed along with 3 Fighters.\n"
"\n"
"Combat Screening: Yellow has 11 vs Green's 9. Yellow may screen 2 ships. "
"Colony Ship automatically screened. CV cannot be targeted while Fighters "
"live. Yellow screens nothing.\n"
"\n"
"Fleet Size Bonus: Neither side has 2x ships. No bonus.\n"
"\n"
"Technologies: Same Tactics. Both have Fighter Tech 1 (B-Class, Attack 5, "
"Defense 0). Both have Cloaking 1, neither has Scanners. No Point Defense."
"\n"
"\n"
"Green Fires A-Class: Base (Attack 7) vs Raider (Defense 0). Needs 1-7. "
"Rolls 5 = Hit. One hit on Raider group.\n"
"\n"
"Yellow Fires A-Class: 2 Raiders (Cloaked, A-Class, Attack 4+1=5) vs BC "
"group. Need 1-4. Roll 10, 8 = both miss. 2 BBs vs BC group. Need 1-4. "
"Roll 7, 2 = one hit on BC group.\n"
"\n"
"Green B-Class: 2 Fighters (5) + 2 BCs (5) vs 3 Yellow Fighters (0). Need "
"1-5. 2 Fighters destroyed.\n"
"\n"
"Yellow B-Class: Fighter (5) vs SY (0). Need 1-5. Hit = SY destroyed.\n"
"\n"
"Green C-Class: 2 CAs (4) vs Yellow CA group (1). Need 1-3. One hit.\n"
"\n"
"Yellow C-Class: 2 CAs (4) vs Green BCs (1). Need 1-3. Two hits. One BC "
"eliminated, other has 1 hit.\n"
"\n"
"Green E-Class: Scout (3) vs Yellow Fighter (0). Need 1-3. Hit = last "
"Fighter destroyed.\n"
"\n"
"Yellow E-Class: CV (3) vs Green Fighter (0). Need 1-3. Hit = one Fighter "
"destroyed.\n"
"\n"
"After Round 1: Yellow has 8 combat-capable ships, Green has 6. Yellow "
"screens CV (now vulnerable). Round 2 proceeds with retreat options "
"available."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:8
msgid "2-Player Small"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:14
msgid ""
"Smallest 2-player map with 17 Deep Space markers and 26 Home System "
"markers per side. Quick games ideal for introducing players to the system"
" or when time is limited. Non-Player Aliens recommended."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:15
msgid ""
"This game is good for introducing players to the system. It is also good "
"for experienced players when they have a time constraint.\n"
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (exception see below).\n"
"• There are 17 Deep Space markers.\n"
"• There are 26 Home System markers on each side. This means that Player 2"
" must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their playing "
"area within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System "
"markers and is fully playable during the game.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex in the row of their "
"Home System that is farthest from their opponent.\n"
"• Hexes outside of the playing area are NOT playable."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:24
msgid "2-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:30
msgid ""
"Standard 2-player map with 34 Deep Space markers and 26 Home System "
"markers per side. The default competitive experience for two players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:31
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are not playable"
" (exception see below).\n"
"• There are 34 Deep Space markers.\n"
"• There are 26 Home System markers on each side. This means that Player 1"
" must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of the playing area "
"within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System markers "
"and is fully playable during the game.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex in the row of their "
"Home System farthest from their opponent.\n"
"• Hexes outside of the playing area are not playable.\n"
"• It is recommended that you use Non-Player Aliens (MRB 18.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:40
msgid "2-Player Large"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:46
msgid ""
"Large 2-player map with 51 Deep Space markers and 26 Home System markers "
"per side. More room for expansion and exploration before contact."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:47
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are not playable"
" (exception see below).\n"
"• There are 51 Deep Space markers.\n"
"• There are 26 Home System markers on each side. This means that Player 2"
" must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of the playing area "
"within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System markers "
"and is fully playable during the game.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex in the row of their "
"Home System farthest from their opponent.\n"
"• Hexes outside of the playing area are not playable.\n"
"• Yeah, you might want to research Exploration..."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:56
msgid "2-Player Extra Large"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:62
msgid ""
"Extra large 2-player map with 98 Deep Space markers. Each player sets up "
"their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions normally used in a "
"4-player game. Exploration technology recommended."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:63
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game.\n"
"• The rest of the map, including unused home regions, gets Deep Space "
"markers. This will use 98 of them.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex within their Home "
"System that is on the edge of the board."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:69
msgid "2-Player \"3D\""
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:75
msgid ""
"Each player sets up in a 4-player quadrant with 46 Deep Space markers "
"between them. The two unused home regions have no System markers but "
"remain traversable — ships entering one side exit from any adjacent hex "
"on the other side, simulating a crude 3D shortcut."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:76
msgid ""
"The title of this scenario promises more than it gives, but you'll see "
"what we mean.\n"
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game.\n"
"• The rest of the map, except unused home regions, gets Deep Space "
"markers. This uses 46 of them.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex within their Home "
"System that is on the edge of the board.\n"
"• The two unused Home Systems get no System markers — they are not in "
"play.\n"
"• More than not being in play, the unused Home Systems need to be thought"
" of as not being there. A player may move a ship into an unused Home "
"System and come out in any other hex adjacent to that unused Home System."
" In essence, it is as if all the hexes adjacent to an unused Home System "
"are adjacent to each other.\n"
"• It takes only 1 Movement Point to move from one hex adjacent to an "
"unused Home System to any other hex adjacent to that Home System.\n"
"• This is an attempt to introduce a 3D element to the game board. Yes, "
"it's crude. Yes, it's simple. But we think it's clever."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:87
msgid "2-Player Massive"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:93
msgid ""
"Massive 2-player map with 98 Deep Space markers. Each player sets up in a"
" 4-player quadrant with 26 Home System markers. Player 1 has 1 extra HS "
"marker, Player 2 has 6 extras placed adjacent to their area."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:94
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up.\n"
"• Player 1 will have one Home System marker and Player 2 will have six "
"Home System markers that do not fit within the area indicated by the "
"line. These should be placed in any hex adjacent to that area.\n"
"• The rest of the map gets Deep Space markers. This will use 98 of them.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex within their Home "
"System that is on the edge of the board."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:101
msgid "\"I Dare You to Play This\""
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:107
msgid ""
"Enormous 2-player map with 98 Deep Space markers. Each player places 26 "
"Home System markers in the first two rows closest to their side, "
"remaining marker in any adjacent hex. A sprawling, long game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:108
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up.\n"
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up.\n"
"• The first two rows closest to each player will be filled by 25 of the "
"Home System markers. The remaining marker should be placed in any hex "
"adjacent to that area.\n"
"• The rest of the map gets Deep Space markers. This will use 98 of them.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex within their Home "
"System that is on the edge of the board."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:116
msgid "2-Player Double Trouble"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:122
msgid ""
"Each player uses all the pieces of their color plus the Home System "
"markers of another color (50 HS markers total per player). 50 Deep Space "
"markers. Each player can use Colony counters of either of their colors. A"
" resource-rich, expansive game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:123
msgid ""
"• Each player uses all the pieces of their color, plus the Home System "
"markers of another color. One non-barren planet and the home planet is "
"removed from each player's additional color.\n"
"• The Home System markers of both colors are mixed together and each "
"player sets up these 50 Home System markers as suggested by the diagram. "
"There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up.\n"
"• The first four rows closest to each player will be filled by their 50 "
"Home System markers.\n"
"• There are 50 Deep Space markers.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex within their Home "
"System that is on the edge of the board.\n"
"• Each player can use the Colony markers of either of their colors."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:132
msgid "2-Player Knife Fight"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:138
msgid ""
"No Deep Space markers — only Home System markers in adjacent quadrants. "
"Both players start with Ship Size 2, Ship Size 3, and Move 2 already "
"researched, plus 4 Scouts and 4 Colony Ships instead of the standard "
"starting forces. Immediate, aggressive conflict."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:139
msgid ""
"• Setup: All 26 Home System markers are used for both players. However no"
" deep space markers are used. One player sets up his home system markers "
"in one of the four quadrants used in the four player game. The other "
"player sets up his markers in quadrant fashion, but adjacent to the first"
" player's quadrant with no deep space markers between them. The home "
"planets are set up on the \"X\".\n"
"• Starting Ships: Both players start with 4 SCs and 4 Colony Ships "
"instead of 3 of each. Other starting units remain as per 1.1.1.\n"
"• Starting Tech: Both players start the game with Ship Size 2, Ship Size "
"3, and Move 2 already researched."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:145
msgid "2-Player Galactic Capitol"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:152
msgid ""
"Standard-sized 2-player map with the Galactic Capitol in the center hex, "
"surrounded by Deep Space. 43 Deep Space markers including the GC. 26 Home"
" System markers per side. Can also be played without the Galactic "
"Capitol."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:153
msgid ""
"• A 2-player game with five rows of Deep Space in between and the "
"Galactic Capitol in the center hex labeled \"GC\" (MRB 28.1).\n"
"• Including the Galactic Capitol there are a total of 43 Deep Space "
"markers.\n"
"• There are 26 Home System markers on each side. This means that both "
"players must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their "
"playing area within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the "
"System markers and is fully playable during the game.\n"
"• This map can also be played without the Galactic Capitol."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:160
msgid "2-Player — Single Talon Map"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:167
msgid ""
"Uses the map board from the game Talon (GMT Games). Two empires set up on"
" opposite sides with 118 Deep Space markers between them. Partial hexes "
"are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:168
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. Two Empires set up on the "
"opposite sides of the board as shown.\n"
"• There are 118 Deep Space markers.\n"
"• Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:174
msgid "2-Player — Both Talon Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:181
msgid ""
"Uses both map boards from Talon placed together. Two empires on opposite "
"sides with 198 Deep Space markers. Partial hexes are not used. An "
"enormous playing field."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:182
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also available through GMT Games. The two boards are placed as above, "
"with two Empires set up on the opposite sides of the map as shown.\n"
"• Each player's Homeworld is placed in a hex marked with an \"H.\" Since "
"there are 30 Home System hexes, each player will have to use 4 of the new"
" Home System markers (marked with a \"v\" on the front side) at random.\n"
"• There are 198 Deep Space markers.\n"
"• Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:189
msgid "2-Player — \"The Belt\" (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:197
msgid ""
"Uses the Talon map with a red Belt region separating two empires. 96 Deep"
" Space markers. Home System markers from a different empire are mixed "
"into the Belt. All Belt and Deep Space planets yield an Alien Technology "
"Card when colonized. Non-Player Aliens on all non-Barren planets. "
"Additional victory condition: having a Colony on 6 Belt planets. Doomsday"
" Machines and Warp Points not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:198
msgid ""
"2.13.1 Setup\n"
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. Two Empires set up on the "
"opposite sides of the board as shown. Each player's Homeworld is placed "
"in a hex marked with an \"H.\" The Home System markers from a different "
"Empire are placed in the red belt between the two Empires. Remove the "
"Homeworld, one non-Barren Planet, one Asteroid counter, and one Nebula "
"before mixing them.\n"
"• There are 96 Deep Space markers.\n"
"\n"
"2.13.2 Special Rules\n"
"• Partial hexes are not used.\n"
"• Do not play with the Amazing Diplomats Empire Advantage.\n"
"• Non-Player Aliens are on all Deep Space and Belt planets, including "
"those that are not Barren. It is possible that you will run out of NPAs "
"in this scenario. If that happens, use a spare counter to mark which "
"planets still have NPAs and how many and draw specific ships when they "
"are attacked.\n"
"• All planets in Deep Space and the Belt give an Alien Technology Card "
"when colonized (MRB 11.0). If you run out of Alien Technology Cards, "
"reshuffle the discards to form a new draw pile.\n"
"• It is recommended that Doomsday Machines (MRB 29.0) and Warp Points "
"(MRB 28.2) are NOT used.\n"
"\n"
"2.13.3 Victory Conditions: In addition to the normal victory conditions, "
"a player can also win by having a Colony on six of the belt planets.\n"
"\n"
"Design Note: This is a longer game, not only because of the size of the "
"map, but because any new Colonies in the belt will be vulnerable. It will"
" be harder for one side to take a dominating lead and both sides should "
"end up deeper in the tech tree."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:213
msgid ""
"Design Note: This is a longer game, not only because of the size of the "
"map, but because any new Colonies in the belt will be vulnerable. It will"
" be harder for one side to take a dominating lead and both sides should "
"end up deeper in the tech tree."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:214
msgid ""
"Design Note: Taking a planet and establishing SYs in the belt to build "
"bigger ships is the key to the game. Ground Units will need to be used "
"since Colony Ships cannot enter the Void."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:219
msgid "2-Player — \"Belt and Void\" (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:228
msgid ""
"Same as The Belt scenario but Deep Space hexes are replaced by a \"Void\""
" zone with strange radiation. Only small ships may enter the Void. Not "
"recommended with Replicators."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:229
msgid ""
"2.14.1 Setup: Everything is the same as The Belt scenario, except that "
"the Deep Space hexes are referred to as the \"Void.\" Add Deep Space "
"markers to every hex of the Void.\n"
"\n"
"2.14.2 Special Rules\n"
"• In the Void, (but not the Belt hexes), there are strange radiation and "
"spatial properties that make it difficult for certain ships to enter.\n"
"• Only Decoys, Minesweepers, Scouts, Destroyers, Raiders, Miners, "
"Transports, Titans, and any advanced versions of those ships may enter "
"the Void.\n"
"• Fighters and Ground Units that are carried by one of the above vessels "
"(or on a Colony) are also allowed.\n"
"• Space Pirates are allowed but captured Non-Player Alien ships are not "
"allowed to move in the Void.\n"
"• Bases and Shipyards can be built at Colonies in the Void and can move "
"in the Void if using the On the Move Empire Advantage.\n"
"• It is not recommended that this scenario be played with Replicators.\n"
"\n"
"Design Note: Taking a planet and establishing SYs in the belt to build "
"bigger ships is the key to the game. Ground Units will need to be used "
"since Colony Ships cannot enter the Void."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:243
msgid "3-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:249
msgid ""
"Standard 3-player map. Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers "
"in one of the regions normally used in a 3-player game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:250
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 3-Player game (denoted by the shading on the game "
"board).\n"
"• The rest of the map (including the two hexes \"behind\" Player 2 and "
"Player 3), gets Deep Space markers. This will use 72 of them.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in the hex marked with an \"X\" in"
" the diagram above.\n"
"• If all players agree, players may place their Homeworlds in any hex of "
"their Home System. Otherwise, they use the hex marked with an \"H\"."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:257
msgid "3-Player Variable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:263
msgid ""
"Random Homeworld placement using a D20 or numbered draw. All Home System "
"and Deep Space markers are mixed together and randomly placed. Often "
"leads to unbalanced maps where diplomacy becomes key."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:264
msgid ""
"• Each player takes their Homeworld and places it randomly. A 20-sided "
"die can be used for this. If one is not available, then pieces of paper "
"numbered 1 to 13 can be drawn out of a cup. The first number rolled/drawn"
" is the row in which your Homeworld will be placed and the second number "
"rolled/drawn is the number of hexes counted over in that row. If a number"
" is rolled that is out of range, then the die is re-rolled until one in "
"range is achieved.\n"
"• All other System markers, both Home System and Deep Space, are mixed "
"together and randomly placed all over the map.\n"
"• This will often lead to unbalanced map layouts. However, for those that"
" love diplomacy, this is all part of the challenge. Those that have "
"weaker positions often gang up on the strong."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:270
msgid "3-Player Teams — 2 vs 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:277
msgid ""
"Standard 3-player map played as 2 vs 1. The team of two operates under "
"UNEASY ALLIANCE rules."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:278
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as the 3-Player Standard scenario (3.1).\n"
"• Mutually agree or determine randomly which two players will be on the "
"same team versus the third player.\n"
"• The two teammates play under the rules as if they have an UNEASY "
"ALLIANCE (1.3.1).\n"
"• A player is eliminated when their Homeworld is destroyed. The team wins"
" as soon as they destroy the Homeworld of the single player. The single "
"player must eliminate both of the other players in order to win. However,"
" the single player does not get the 30 CP conquering bonus listed in the "
"Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition (1.1.8).\n"
"• Each of the allied players collect income normally, but all of their "
"ships and technology cost 1.5 times normal (round up). That means a Scout"
" would cost 9 instead of 6, a Destroyer would cost 14 instead of 9, and "
"Tactics 1 Technology would cost 23 instead of 15 (for example).\n"
"• Maintenance and turn order bid would still be normal cost."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:287
msgid "3-Player Teams — 2 vs 1 with Empire Advantages"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:295
msgid ""
"Same as 3-Player Teams 2 vs 1 but with Empire Advantages. The team pays "
"normal cost. The solo player draws 6 and chooses 4."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:296
msgid ""
"The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given in the "
"3-Player Teams – 2 vs 1 scenario (3.3), with the following exceptions:\n"
"• The team of two players pays the normal cost in CP for everything. They"
" do not have to pay 1.5 times the normal amount.\n"
"• The team of two players does not get any Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0), "
"but the single player draws six Empire Advantage cards and gets to choose"
" four of them. As normal, these Empire Advantages remain secret until "
"used in such a way that they would be revealed or a Colony is invaded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:302
msgid "3-Player Teams — 2 vs 1 with Replicators"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:310
msgid ""
"Same as 3-Player Teams 2 vs 1. Replicator on the solo side. Replicator "
"Colonies start at 1 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:311
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as the 3-Player Teams - 2 vs 1 scenario (3.3).\n"
"• Mutually agree or determine trandomly which two players will be on the "
"same team versus the third player.\n"
"• The two teammates operate under an UNEASY ALLIANCE (1.3.1).\n"
"• In this game the Replicator's Colonies start at 1 CP instead of Start. "
"They can still be bombarded back down to Start and will then grow to 1 CP"
" – 3 CP – Full.\n"
"• A player is eliminated when their Homeworld is destroyed. The team wins"
" as soon as they destroy the Replicator player's Homeworld. The "
"Replicator player must eliminate both of the other players in order to "
"win. However, the Replicator player does not get the 30 CP conquering "
"bonus listed in the Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition (1.1.8.)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:319
msgid "4-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:325
msgid ""
"Standard 4-player map. Each player sets up 26 Home System markers in one "
"of the four outlined quadrants. 46 Deep Space markers fill the center."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:326
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game (denoted by the outlined sections on the"
" game board).\n"
"• The rest of the map gets Deep Space markers. This will use 46 of them.\n"
"• Each player places their home planet in any hex within their Home "
"System that is on the edge of the board."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:332
msgid "4-Player Variable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:338
msgid ""
"Same as the Variable 3-Player Map. Random Homeworld placement with all "
"markers mixed and placed randomly."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:339
msgid "• Setup is the same as the Variable 3-Player Map (3.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:343
msgid "4-Player Team Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:350
msgid ""
"Standard 4-player map played as 2 vs 2. Teams determined randomly. "
"Players choose UNEASY ALLIANCE or BLOOD BROTHERS."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:351
msgid ""
"• Set up is the same as the Standard 4-Player Map (4.1).\n"
"• Mutually agree or determine randomly what the teams will be.\n"
"• Teammates can be diagonally across from each other or next to each "
"other depending on personal preference.\n"
"• Players must decide to play UNEASY ALLIANCE or BLOOD BROTHERS.\n"
"• UNEASY ALLIANCE: Teammates may never stack ships of any kind in the "
"same hex and may not use each other's MS Pipelines.\n"
"• BLOOD BROTHERS: Teammates execute their turns at the same time, may "
"stack together, may attack together, and may use each other's MS "
"Pipelines for movement. However, they may not share research or CPs.\n"
"• In either case, the teammates win or lose the game together."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:361
msgid "4-Player Teams with Empire Advantages"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:369
msgid ""
"Same as 4-Player Team Play. All players draw Empire Advantages as per the"
" normal method."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:370
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as 4-Player Team Play (4.3).\n"
"• All players draw Empire Advantages as per either normal method (MRB "
"10.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:375
msgid "4-Player Teams — 3 vs 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:382
msgid ""
"Standard 4-player map played as 3 vs 1. The three-player team operates as"
" BLOOD BROTHERS. Solo player gets double income and extra Empire "
"Advantages."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:383
msgid ""
"The set up and rules for this scenario are the same as given in the "
"4-Player Team Play scenario (4.3), with the following exceptions:\n"
"• Instead of 2 vs 2, this scenario is 3 vs 1.\n"
"• The three players that are on the same team are operating under BLOOD "
"BROTHERS (1.3.2).\n"
"• The player on their own receives double the normal CP income from all "
"colonies except their home planet. Example: If a player has a 30 CP Home "
"Planet, two 3 CP colonies, one of which was connected by an MS Pipeline, "
"the player would get 43 CP.\n"
"• The single player draws three Empire Advantage cards (MRB 10.0) and "
"picks one. The three-player team draws a pool of five Empire Advantage "
"cards and each player will get to pick one of them.\n"
"• Each of the players on the three-player team starts with the "
"technologies Terraforming 1 and Scanners 1.\n"
"• The player on their own must destroy all three of the enemy home "
"worlds.\n"
"\n"
"WARNING: This has the possibility of becoming a long scenario.\n"
"\n"
"Design Note: This has the possibility of becoming a long scenario."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:397
msgid "4-Player Teams — 3 vs 1 with Replicators"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:405
msgid ""
"Same as 4-Player Teams 3 vs 1. The Replicator player must be on the team "
"with 3 players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:406
msgid ""
"The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given in the "
"4-Player Teams – 3 vs 1 scenario (4.5), with the following exceptions:\n"
"• The Replicator player must be on the team with 3 players.\n"
"• The Replicator player draws two Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0) and keeps "
"one while the other two players on their team draw three Empire "
"Advantages total and each keep one."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:412
msgid "4-Player Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:418
msgid ""
"Smaller Home Systems (14 markers per player) with 94 Deep Space markers. "
"A Deep Space-heavy map with emphasis on exploration and expansion."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:419
msgid ""
"• There are 14 Home System Markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, five planets, one "
"Barren Planet, and seven Mineral counters.\n"
"• Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an \"H\" and "
"their remaining 13 Home System markers are mixed and placed within 3 "
"hexes of the home planet.\n"
"• The rest of the hexes get Deep Space markers — 94 will be used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:425
msgid "4-Player Three Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:431
msgid ""
"25 Home System markers per player (minus one 5-Mineral). 50 Deep Space "
"markers between the quadrants. Bottom row not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:432
msgid ""
"• There are 25 Home System markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player removes one 5-Mineral marker, then places "
"their Homeworld in a hex marked with an \"H\" then the remaining 24 Home "
"System markers for each player are mixed and placed within the boundaries"
" shown in the diagram.\n"
"• The row of hexes at the bottom of the map do not get markers and are "
"not used.\n"
"• There are 50 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:438
msgid "4-Player Four Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:444
msgid ""
"Same as Three Row Deep Space but with 4 rows of Deep Space. 24 Home "
"System markers per player."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenarios.py:445
msgid ""
"• There are 25 Home System markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player removes one 5-Mineral marker, then places "
"their Homeworld in a hex marked with an \"H\" then the remaining 24 Home "
"System markers for each player are mixed and placed within the "
"boundaries.\n"
